# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: english-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] A second edition of *A Dictionary of Canadianisms on Historical Principles* (DCHP-2), was then created by expanding and partially revising the first edition's data set.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] DCHP-2 was published in 2017 as an academic project by the University of British Columbia, and is only available as a free-access online dictionary.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] A third edition (DCHP-3), this time in mobile-friendly format, was released in 2025 with 181 new meanings relating to minoritized groups and the originally more informal vocabulary.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The origins of the first Canadian Dictionary (DCHP-1) can be linked to American Lexicographer Charles Julien Lovell just after WW2 in 1946.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Predating this, the American OED dictionary included the small number of Canadian words found in their research as was the practice during this time for larger varieties.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Lovell, working at the time for the University of Chicago and the Dictionary of Americanisms, felt that there was a true distinction between American words and Canadian ones.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] This led Lovell to create a separate file for words that he deemed to be Canadian as he traversed across the country.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] In 1954, after creation of the Canadian Linguistic Association, Lovell proposed his idea of the creation of the first Canadian Dictionary, and shortly after submitted an article on the “Lexicographical Challenges of Canadian English”.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] In March 1960, funding was granted to create the first Canadian Dictionary, DCHP-1 (Dictionary of Canadianisms on Historical Principles).Charles Lovell died just weeks later.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The lead of the project would then be taken on and headed by Lovell's colleague and friend, Walter Spencer Avis.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] A professor of English at the Royal Military College in Kingston, Ontario.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Without intention, Avis, came to become a dictionary editor and leader to complete DCHP-1.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Along with him, Patrick Drysdale, Chuck Crate, Douglas Leechman, and Mathew Scargill (these names, with Avis and Lovell would become known as the big six of creating Canadian English).
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Drysdale focused on working with the publisher of the dictionary in Toronto, W.J.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Gage publishing and relayed information to the team.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Avis, Crate, And Leechman were responsible for controlling the majority of the information brought in through slips.> Scargill, the “director of the Lexicographical Centre in Victoria'' was the promoter and organizer of the DCHP.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The Publisher, Gage, requested that four versions of the dictionary were to be made: the Beginning Dictionary, Intermediate Dictionary, Senior Dictionary, and the Complete version DCHP-1.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The final dictionary was completed just in time for Canadians' Centennial year In November 1967.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] In 2006, after almost 40 years of existence without any updates, work on a new edition was started.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Nelson Education Ltd., which had acquired Gage Ltd. and with it the rights to the DCHP-1 had been actively seeking collaborators in academia to produce a new edition of the DCHP-1.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] This project, DCHP-2, was proposed at a conference on Canadian English in January 2005, and formally commenced at the University of British Columbia's Department of English in August 2006, after a year of preparatory work.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Since 2009, DCHP-2 has had no association with Nelson Ltd. or any other publisher and had been a purely academic project.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Completed in 2011 after automatic scanning and manual proofreading by a team at UBC, *DCHP*-1 was republished in open access as of 2013, thanks to Nelson Ltd.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] 2013), and is available as a free website, *DCHP*-1 Online.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The second edition was edited by Stefan Dollinger (editor-in-chief) and Margery Fee (associate editor) and includes features not part of the first edition: a six-way classification system for Canadianisms, the Dictionary Editing Tool, and the Bank of Canadian English (BCE), a quotation database.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The process of digitization started with the scanning and of the first edition of the dictionary (DCHP-1).
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The online version of DCHP-1 was made publicly accessible in 2013.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The main data collection phase for the DCHP-2 lasted from 2007 to 2010 and included 36,000 new citations derived from the 7,000 new potential headwords found in The Canadian Oxford Dictionary and other sources.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Potential headwords and citations were cross-checked with other varieties of English using web data and entered into the Bank of Canadian English, a quotation filing system, to be proofread and edited.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The potential headwords and citations were then classified into one of the six categories of Canadianisms according to their distinctive histories in Canada, cultural significance, or usage frequency.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] DCHP-2 was released online on 17 March 2017.{{source needed}} The launch coincided with the 57th anniversary of Charles J.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Lovell's passing, the founding editor of DCHP-1.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] DCHP-1 was launched as a Centennial project; DCHP-2 was launched as a Sesquicentennial contribution with the goal of lifting the discussion about Canadianisms, and about Canadian English more generally, on an empirically sounder footing.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The Third Edition was released on 15 May 2025.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Its code base was rewritten to accommodate mobile phone use and includes an editorial update of 181 meanings for a total of 12,000 headwords and 14,500 meanings from 1500 to 2025.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] Work began in 2022 and lasted through May 2025.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The third edition update focuses on underrepresented groups, e.g.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] First Nations (lahal, kokum, skoden), and vocabulary from informal origins, e.g. urban slang (freezie, ding, levidrome) and rural slang (klick, hang a larry, shit-kicking).
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-canadianisms-on-historical-principles] The *Toronto Star* referred to it as a great "birthday gift for the nation" of Canada, *The Globe and Mail* lauded its detail (e.g. the entry on *eh*, which is almost 5000 words long) and the CBC The National Newscast featured DCHP-2 in April 2017 as the topic of its cultural news item of the day.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] There was dissatisfaction with the dictionaries of the period, so in June 1746 a group of London booksellers contracted Johnson to write a dictionary for the sum of 1,500 guineas (£1,575), equivalent to about £300,000 in 2025.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson took seven years to complete the work, although he had claimed he could finish it in three.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] He did so single-handedly, with only clerical assistance to copy the illustrative quotations that he had marked in books.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson produced several revised editions during his life.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Until the completion of the *Oxford English Dictionary* 173 years later, Johnson's was viewed as the pre-eminent English dictionary.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] According to Walter Jackson Bate, the Dictionary "easily ranks as one of the greatest single achievements of scholarship, and probably the greatest ever performed by one individual who laboured under anything like the disadvantages in a comparable length of time".
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In earlier times, books had been regarded with something approaching veneration, but by the mid-eighteenth century this was no longer the case.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The rise of literacy among the general public, combined with the technical advances in the mechanics of printing and bookbinding, meant that for the first time, books, texts, maps, pamphlets and newspapers were widely available to the general public at a reasonable cost.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Such an explosion of the printed word demanded a set pattern of grammar, definition, and spelling for those words.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] This could be achieved by means of an authoritative dictionary of the English language.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In 1746, a consortium of London's most successful printers, including Robert Dodsley and Thomas Longman – none could afford to undertake it alone – set out to satisfy and capitalise on this need by the ever-increasing reading and writing public.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's dictionary was not the first English dictionary, nor even among the first dozen.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Over the previous 150 years more than twenty dictionaries had been published in England, the oldest of these being a Latin-English "wordbook" by Sir Thomas Elyot published in 1538.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The next to appear was by Richard Mulcaster, a headmaster, in 1583.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] It was the first English dictionary to use quotations ("illustrations") to give meaning to the word; in none of these dictionaries so far were there any actual definitions of words.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] This was to change, to a small extent, in schoolmaster Robert Cawdrey's *Table Alphabeticall*, published in 1604.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Though it contained only 2,449 words, and no word beginning with the letters *W*, *X*, or *Y*, this was the first monolingual English dictionary.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Several more dictionaries followed: in Latin, English, French and Italian.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Benjamin Martin's *Lingua Britannica Reformata* (1749) and Ainsworth's *Thesaurus Linguae Latinae* (1737) are both significant, in that they define entries in separate senses, or aspects, of the word.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The problem with these dictionaries was that they tended to be little more than poorly organised and poorly researched glossaries of "hard words": words that were technical, foreign, obscure or antiquated.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Perhaps the greatest single fault of these early lexicographers was, as historian Henry Hitchings put it, that they "failed to give sufficient sense of [the English] language as it appeared *in use*." In that sense Dr.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's dictionary was the first to comprehensively document the English lexicon.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's dictionary was prepared at 17 Gough Square, London, an eclectic household, between the years of 1746 and 1755.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] By 1747 Johnson had written his *Plan of a Dictionary of the English Language*, which spelled out his intentions and proposed methodology for preparing his document.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's *Plan* received the patronage of Philip Stanhope, 4th Earl of Chesterfield but not to Johnson's pleasure.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Chesterfield did not care about praise, but was instead interested by Johnson's abilities.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Seven years after first meeting Johnson to discuss the work, Chesterfield wrote two anonymous essays in *The World* that recommended the *Dictionary*.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] However, Johnson did not appreciate the tone of the essay, and he felt that Chesterfield had not made good on his promise to be the work's patron.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The words "Samuel Johnson" and "English Language" were printed in red; the rest was printed in black.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The preface and headings were set in 4.6 mm "English" type, the text—double columned—was set in a typeface like Caslon.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] This first edition of the dictionary contained a 42,773-word list, to which only a few more were added in subsequent editions.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] One of Johnson's important innovations was to illustrate the meanings of his words by literary quotation, of which there are around 114,000, from around 500 authors.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The authors most frequently cited by Johnson include Shakespeare, Milton and Dryden.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Furthermore, Johnson, unlike Bailey, added notes on a word's usage, rather than being merely descriptive.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Unlike most modern lexicographers, Johnson introduced humour or prejudice into quite a number of his definitions.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] On a more serious level, Johnson's work showed a heretofore unseen meticulousness.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The original goal was to publish the dictionary in two folio volumes, A–K and L–Z, but that soon proved unwieldy, unprofitable, and unrealistic.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Subsequent printings ran to four volumes; even these formed a stack 10 inches (25 cm) tall, and weighed in at nearly 21 pounds (9.5 kg).
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In addition to the sheer physical heft of Johnson's dictionary, came the equally hefty price: £4/10/– (equivalent to approximately £880 in 2025).
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] So discouraging was the price that by 1784, thirty years after the first edition was published, when the dictionary had by then run through five editions, only about 6,000 copies were in circulation—an average sale of 200 books a year for thirty years.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's etymologies would be considered poor by modern standards, and he gave little guide to pronunciation; one example being "Cough: A convulsion of the lungs, vellicated by some sharp serosity.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Much of his dictionary was prescriptivist.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] It was also linguistically conservative, advocating traditional spellings such as *publick* rather than the simpler spellings that would be favoured 73 years later by Noah Webster.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The dictionary is in alphabetical order according to the eighteenth-century English alphabet.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In the eighteenth century, the letters I and J were considered different forms of the same letter; the same with letters U and V.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] As a result, in Johnson's dictionary the word jargon comes before the word idle, and vagabond comes before ultimate.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In spite of its shortcomings, the dictionary was far and away the best of its day.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Its scope and structure were carried forward in dictionaries that followed, including Noah Webster's *Webster's Dictionary* in 1828 and the *Oxford English Dictionary* later in the same century.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Immediately after publication "The *Dictionary* was enthusiastically written up in important periodicals such as the *London Magazine* and—none too surprisingly—the *Gentleman's Magazine*.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In the latter it received an eight-page notice".
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Furthermore, Johnson's approach was not 'sufficiently grammatical'".
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] He gave up the house in Gough Square in March 1759, probably for lack of funds.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Yet, just as Johnson was plunging into another trough of despondency, the reputation of the *Dictionary* at last brought reward.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In July 1762 Johnson was granted a state pension of £300 a year by the twenty-four-year-old monarch, George III.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] As lexicography developed, faults were found with Johnson's work: "From an early stage there were noisy detractors.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Perhaps the loudest of them was John Horne Tooke ...
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's dictionary was made when etymology was largely based on guesswork.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] His Classical leanings led him to prefer spellings that pointed to Latin or Greek sources, "while his lack of sound scholarship prevented him from detecting their frequent errors".
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] For example, he preferred the spelling *ache* over *ake* as he wrongly thought it came from the Greek *achos*.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Some of his spelling choices were also inconsistent: "while retaining the Latin *p* in *receipt* he left it out of *deceit*; he spelled *deign* one way and *disdain* another; he spelled *uphill* but *downhil*, *muckhill* but *dunghil*, *instill* but *distil*, *inthrall* but *disenthral*".
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's general rule, therefore, can only take place where custom has not plainly decided.' Nevertheless, Walker scrupulously followed Johnson's explanations of words, as did many contemporary dictionaries.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Despite the criticisms, "The influence of the *Dictionary* was sweeping.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson established both a methodology for how dictionaries should be put together and a paradigm for how entries should be presented.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Anyone who sought to create a dictionary, post-Johnson, did so in his shadow." "In his history of the *Oxford English Dictionary*, Simon Winchester asserts of its eighteenth-century predecessor that 'by the end of the century every educated household had, or had access to, the great book.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In 2005, the Royal Mint issued a commemorative fifty pence coin celebrating the 250th anniversary of the dictionary's publication.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's influence was not confined to Britain and English: "The president of the Florentine Accademia declared that the *Dictionary* would be 'a perpetual Monument of Fame to the Author, an Honour to his own Country in particular, and a general Benefit to the Republic of Letters'.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's work served as a model for lexicographers abroad.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] It is no surprise that his friend Giuseppe Baretti chose to make the *Dictionary* the model for his Italian—English dictionary of 1760, and for his Spanish dictionary nearly two decades later but there are numerous examples of influence beyond Johnson's own circle.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The *Dictionary* was exported to America.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] "The American adoption of the *Dictionary* was a momentous event not just in its history, but in the history of lexicography.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In 1789 [Webster] declared that 'Great Britain, whose children we are, and whose language we speak, should no longer be *our* standard; for the taste of her writers is already corrupted, and her language on the decline.'" "Where Webster found fault with Johnson, Joseph Worcester saluted him ...
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In 1846 he completed his *Universal and Critical Dictionary of the English Language*.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Legislators are much occupied with ascertaining 'first meanings', with trying to secure the literal sense of their predecessors' legislation ...
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's dictionary came out in two forms.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The first was the 1755 *Folio* edition, which came in two large volumes on 4 April.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The folio edition also features full literary quotes by those authors that Johnson quoted, such as Dryden and Shakespeare.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] It was followed a few weeks later by a second edition published in 165 weekly parts.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The third edition was published in 1765, but it was the fourth, which came out in 1773 which included significant revisions by Johnson of the original work.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The *Abridged* edition came out in 1756 in two octavo volumes with entries, "abstracted from the folio edition by the author", laid out as two columns per page.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The abridged version did not feature the literary quotes, just the author quoted.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] This made it cheaper to produce and buy.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] It sold over a thousand copies a year for the next 30 years bringing "The Dictionary" to the reach of every literate home.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's *Dictionary* has been available in replica editions for some years.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The entire first *Folio* editions of 1755 1st edition and 1773 4th edition are available on *Johnson's Dictionary Online*, a project funded by the National Endowment for the Humanities and created by a team of scholars at the University of Central Florida.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] This version is the first fully searchable online edition.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The Preface to the *Dictionary* is available on Project Gutenberg.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] In Melville's *Moby-Dick*, the narrator mentions using Johnson's dictionary to aid him in his leviathanic undertaking: "Fain am I to stagger to this emprise under the weightiest words of the dictionary.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] At the end of Chapter 1 of *Vanity Fair* by William Makepeace Thackeray, Becky Sharp disdainfully throws a copy of Johnson's *Dictionary* out the window.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson's Great Dictionary" appears as a plot device in the 1944 Sherlock Holmes film *The Pearl of Death*, starring Basil Rathbone and Nigel Bruce.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] Johnson had given his only manuscript to the Prince of Wales and it was presumably destroyed by Blackadder's apprentice dogsbody Baldrick.
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The manuscript is later found intact, only for Johnson to discover he had forgotten to include the word "sausage".
[src:english-language/a-dictionary-of-the-english-language] The episode ends with Baldrick throwing the dictionary into the fire.
[src:english-language/a-new-english-dictionary] Unlike previous dictionaries, which had focused on documenting difficult words, *A New English Dictionary* was one of the first to focus on words in common usage.
[src:english-language/a-new-english-dictionary] It was also the first to be written by a professional lexicographer.
[src:english-language/a-new-english-dictionary] Kersey later continued his lexicographic career by enlarging Edward Phillips' *The New World of English Words* in 1706 and editing the *Dictionarium Anglo-Britannicum* in 1708.
[src:english-language/a-new-english-dictionary] The original title of the *Oxford English Dictionary* was *A New English Dictionary on Historical Principles*, and it was sometimes given the abbreviation *NED*, for *New English Dictionary*.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] However, a minority of linguists argue that the vernacular shares so many characteristics with African creole languages spoken around the world that it could have originated as a creole (or semi-creole) language, distinct from the English language, before re-converging with English.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] African-American Vernacular English (AAVE) may be considered a dialect, ethnolect, and sociolect.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] While it is clear that there is a strong historical relationship between AAVE and earlier Southern U.S. dialects, the origins of AAVE are still a matter of debate.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] The presiding theory among linguists is that AAVE has always been a dialect of English, meaning that it originated from earlier English dialects rather than from English-based creole languages that "decreolized" back into English.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Linguist John McWhorter maintains that the contribution of West African languages to AAVE is minimal.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] According to this theory, these captives first developed pidgins or simplified mixtures of languages.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Because pidgins form from close contact between speakers of different languages, the slave trade would have been exactly such a situation.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Creolist John Dillard quotes, for example, slave ship captain William Smith describing the sheer diversity of mutually unintelligible languages just in The Gambia.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] By 1715, an African pidgin was reproduced in novels by Daniel Defoe, in particular, *The Life of Colonel Jacque*.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] In 1721, Cotton Mather conducted the first attempt at recording the speech of slaves in his interviews regarding the practice of smallpox inoculation.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] By the time of the American Revolution, varieties among slave creoles were not quite mutually intelligible.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] The abolitionist papers before the war form a rich corpus of examples of plantation creole.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] In *Army Life in a Black Regiment* (1870), Thomas Wentworth Higginson detailed many features of his African-American soldiers' language.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Opponents of the creole theory suggest that such pidgins or creoles existed but simply died out without directly contributing to modern AAVE.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Many pronunciation features set AAVE apart from other forms of American English (particularly General American).
[src:english-language/aave-accents] John McWhorter argues that what truly unites all AAVE accents is a uniquely wide-ranging intonation pattern or "melody", which characterizes even the most "neutral" or light African-American accent.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] A handful of multisyllabic words in AAVE differ from General American in their stress placement so that, for example, *police*, *guitar*, and *Detroit* are pronounced with initial stress instead of ultimate stress.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] The following are phonological differences in AAVE vowel and consonant sounds.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Final consonant groups or clusters in AAVE have been examined as evidence of the systematic nature of this language variety, governed by specific rules.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] These analyses have been utilized to bolster arguments concerning the historical origins of AAVE.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Consonant cluster reduction is a phonological process where a final consonant group or cluster, consisting of two adjacent consonant sounds, is simplified or reduced to a single consonant sound.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] The analysis of consonant cluster reduction in AAVE assumes that, initially, final clusters are present and intact in the language.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] For example, the word "tes" in AAVE originates from "test", with the final "t" of the "st" consonant cluster being deleted in word-final position.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] McWhorter discusses an accent continuum from "a 'deep' Black English through a 'light' Black English to standard English," saying the sounds on this continuum may vary from one African American speaker to the next or even in a single speaker from one situational context to the next.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Although AAVE does not necessarily have the simple past-tense marker of other English varieties (that is, the *-ed* of "work*ed*"), it does have an optional tense system with at least four aspects of the past tense and two aspects of the future tense.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] The dialect uses several tense–aspect–mood markers integrated into the predicate phrase, including *gon* or *gonna* (future tense), *done* (completive aspect), *be* (habitual aspect, state of being), and *been* (durative aspect).
[src:english-language/aave-accents] These can function separately or in conjunction.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] means "he finished work a long time ago".
[src:english-language/aave-accents] means "until recently, he worked over a long period of time".
[src:english-language/aave-accents] The latter example shows one of the most distinctive features of AAVE: the use of *be* to indicate that performance of the verb is of a habitual nature.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] In most other American English dialects, this can only be expressed unambiguously by using adverbs such as *usually*.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] This aspect-marking form of *been* or BIN is stressed and semantically distinct from the unstressed form: *She BIN running* ('She has been running for a long time') and *She been running* ('She has been running').
[src:english-language/aave-accents] This aspect has been given several names, including *perfect phase*, *remote past*, and *remote phase* (this article uses the third).
[src:english-language/aave-accents] As shown above, *been* places action in the distant past.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] However, when *been* is used with stative verbs or gerund forms, *been* shows that the action began in the distant past and that it is continuing now.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Rickford (1999) suggests that a better translation when used with stative verbs is "for a long time".
[src:english-language/aave-accents] For instance, in response to "I like your new dress", one might hear *Oh, I been had this dress*, meaning that the speaker has had the dress for a long time and that it isn't new.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] means "I bought her clothes a long time ago".
[src:english-language/aave-accents] means "I've been buying her clothes for a long time".
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Auxiliaries in African American Vernacular English are related in a typical pattern.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] They can be grouped into negative forms and affirmative forms for each of the words.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] For example, "had" is an affirmative form, while "hatn" is the corresponding negative form.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] These same auxiliaries can be used to mark sentences for the anterior aspect.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] As another example, *was* marks type 1 sentences, which by default are present tense, and transforms them to a time before the present.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Take, for instance, "She at home": the word *was* can be inserted to mark this sentence, making the marked equivalent "She was at home".
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Auxiliaries such as these also have opposing negative and affirmative forms.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] In its negative form the auxiliary verb "wadn" is used to convey the opposing affirmative form.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] The irrealis mood marker *be*, having no intrinsic tense refers to a current or future event that may be less than real.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] The dialect uses double modals, such as *might could*, which can function in various ways, including as adverbs.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] While AAVE shares these with Creole languages, early recordings of African Nova Scotian English, Samaná English, and recordings of former slaves indicate that negation was likely inherited from nonstandard colonial English.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] AAVE shares most of its lexicon with other varieties of English, particularly that of informal and Southern dialects, such as, the relatively recent use of *y'all*.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] The main sources for new words are combining, shifting, shortening, blending, borrowing, and creating.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] It has also been suggested that some of the vocabulary unique to AAVE has its origin in West African languages.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] However, etymology is often difficult to trace and, without a trail of recorded usage, these proposed origins cannot be considered proven.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Early AAVE and Gullah contributed a number of words of African origin to the American English mainstream, including *gumbo*, *goober*, *yam*, and *banjo*.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Compounding in AAVE is a very common method in creating new vocabulary.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] The most common type of compounding is the noun–noun combination, followed by adjective–noun combination.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] AAVE also combines adjectives with other adjectives less frequently, but more often than in standard American English.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] AAVE has also contributed slang expressions such as *cool* and *hip*, *to dig*, *jazz*, *tote*, and *bad-mouth*, a calque from Mandinka.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] In many cases, the proposed West African etymologies are not recognized by linguists or the *Oxford English Dictionary*.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Innovative African American slang is often formed by combining, shifting, shortening, blending, and borrowing English words and phrases that are regarded as informal.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] AAVE also has words that either are not found in other American English dialects or that have strikingly different meanings.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] For example, there are several words in AAVE referring to White people that are not part of mainstream American English; these include *gray* as an adjective for Whites (as in *gray dude*), possibly from the color of Confederate uniforms; and *paddy*, an extension of the slang use for "Irish".
[src:english-language/aave-accents] "Red bone" is another example of this, usually referring to light-skinned African Americans.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] "Ofay", which is pejorative, is another general term for a White person; it might derive from the Ibibio word *afia*, which means "light-colored", from the Yoruba word *ofe*, spoken in hopes of disappearing from danger.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] However, most dictionaries simply say its etymology is unknown.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] AAVE has also contributed many words and phrases to other varieties of English, including *chill out*, *main squeeze*, *soul*, *funky*, and *threads*.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] African-American Vernacular English has influenced the development of other dialects of English.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] The AAVE accent, New York accent, and Spanish-language accents have together yielded the sound of New York Latino English, some of whose speakers use an accent indistinguishable from an AAVE one.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] AAVE has also influenced certain Chicano accents and Liberian Settler English, directly derived from the AAVE of the original 16,000 African Americans who migrated to Liberia in the 1800s.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] In the United States, urban youth participating in hip-hop culture or marginalized as ethnic minorities may also adopt AAVE, or prominent elements of it: for example, Southeast-Asian Americans embracing hip-hop identities.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Internet slang has borrowed heavily from AAVE, which has often been characterized as cultural appropriation.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] The term *blaccent* broadly refers to the accent associated with AAVE, but more often refers to the use of AAVE by non-African American speakers.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Early research on African-American Vernacular English took place in cities such as New York, Los Angeles, and Chicago.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] These studies concluded that AAVE was linguistically homogenous, or spoken roughly the same way everywhere around the country.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Later sociolinguists found that these cities lacked the influence of the rural South and that earlier studies had not considered the representation of the Southern United States.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] While AAVE began as mostly rural and Southern, today it is mostly urban and nationally widespread.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Its more recent urban features are now diffusing back into rural areas.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Urban AAVE alone is intensifying with the grammatical features exemplified in these sentences: "He be the best" (intensified equative *be*), "She be done had her baby" (resultative *be done*), and "They come hollerin" (indignant *come*).
[src:english-language/aave-accents] On the other hand, rural AAVE alone shows certain features too, such as: "I was a-huntin" (*a*-prefixing); "It riz above us" (different irregular forms); and "I want for to eat it" (*for to* complement).
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Use of the word *bees* in place of *be* to mean *is* or *are* in standard English, as in the sentence "That's the way it bees", is one of the rarest of all deep AAVE features today.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Most middle-class AAVE speakers would recognize the verb *bees* as part of only a deep "Southern" or "country" speaker's vocabulary.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] There are at least 10 distinct regional accents in AAVE.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Memphis, Atlanta, and Research Triangle AAVE incorporates the dress vowel raising and face vowel lowering associated with white Southern accents.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Louis AAVE are developing, since the mid-twentieth century, an iconic merger of the vowels in square and nurse, making *there* sound like *thurr*.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Californian AAVE often lacks a cot–caught merger, especially before nasals.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Regional patterns of pronunciation and word choice are also apparent on social media.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] There is general uniformity of AAVE grammar, despite its vast geographic spread across the whole country.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] This may be due in part to relatively recent migrations of some African Americans out of the American South (see Great Migration and Second Great Migration) as well as to long-term racial segregation that kept these speakers living together in largely homogeneous communities.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] African-American Vernacular suffers from persistent stigma and negative social evaluation in American culture.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] By definition, as a vernacular dialect of English, AAVE has not received the social prestige of a standard dialect, leading to widespread and long-standing misconceptions that it is a grammatically inferior form of English, which linguistics research of the twentieth century has debunked.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Some of the harshest criticism of AAVE or its use has come from African Americans themselves.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] A conspicuous example was the "Pound Cake speech", in which Bill Cosby criticized fellow African Americans for various social behaviors, including the way they talked.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Educators traditionally have attempted to eliminate AAVE usage through the public education system, perceiving the dialect as grammatically defective.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] In 1974, the teacher-led Conference on College Composition and Communication issued a position statement affirming students' rights to their own dialects and the validity of all dialects.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Mainstream linguistics has long agreed with this view about dialects.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] This program lasted three years and then died off.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Many notable genres, styles, and movements within African-American music, and cultural and artistic movements or subcultures, are offshoots of African-American culture.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] The genres of Christian spirituals, blues, jazz, R&B, and hip-hop all originated from Black Americans.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] AAVE, thus, is the typical dialect employed in their lyrics, often even among these genres' non-Black musicians.
[src:english-language/aave-accents] Two such cultural movements with particular international prominence are jazz culture of the late 1930s and 1940s (with its associated AAVE slang, jive talk) and hip-hop culture of the late 20th century into the present.
[src:english-language/abercraf-english] Abercraf English is distinct from other accents in its county, such as the one spoken in Myddfai, due to separation by the Brecon Beacons, creating a substantial communication barrier between the two localities.
[src:english-language/abercraf-english] It is more appropriate to associate it with neighbouring Swansea Valley, particularly the speech in northern areas (esp.
[src:english-language/abercraf-english] Ystalyfera and Ystradgynlais) since they are more similar to Abercraf than ones in its county.
[src:english-language/abercraf-english] This could be seen from a survey where speakers could not discern the origins of the speech of Ystradgynlais and their hometown, but were able to discern Cwmtwrch with other villages in the valley.
[src:english-language/abercraf-english] Abercraf was entirely Welsh-speaking until World War II, when English-speaking evacuees settled in the village.
[src:english-language/abercraf-english] It is a relatively young acquired dialect.
[src:english-language/abercraf-english] This can be seen from generally less assimilation and elision and clear articulation unlike other accents in Powys or Swansea.
[src:english-language/abercraf-english] As a more modern accent, it is restricted to the last two to three generations, with younger people being much more likely to speak it — though much of their daily life is conducted in Welsh, leading English to be taught as a second language.
[src:english-language/abercraf-english] Abercraf English is non-rhotic; /r/ is only pronounced before a vowel.
[src:english-language/abercraf-english] Like RP, linking and intrusive R is present in the system.
[src:english-language/abercraf-english] On the other hand, the vowel system varies greatly from RP, unlike its consonants, which is stable in many English accents around the world.
[src:english-language/abercraf-english] The offsets of the fronting diphthongs are near-close [ɪ], whereas the offsets of the backing diphthongs are close [u].
[src:english-language/abercraf-english] Abercraf has kept some distinctions between diphthong–monophthong pronunciations; they are shared among other south Welsh dialects such as Port Talbot.
[src:english-language/abercraf-english] Abercraf English generally follows West Glamorgan lexical incidence patterns.
[src:english-language/abercraf-english] The vowel /ə/ is not elided, thus *factory*, *mandarin*, *reference* always have three syllables, unlike many accents such as RP or even Port Talbot.
[src:english-language/abercraf-english] Abercraf English is considered to have a 'sing-song' or 'lilting' intonation due to having high amount of pitch on an unstressed post-tonic syllable, as well as pre-tonic syllables having a great degree of freedom, with a continuous rising pitch being common.
[src:english-language/ablaut] In linguistics, the **Indo-European ablaut** (/ˈæb.laʊt/ *AB-lowt*, from German *Ablaut* pronounced [ˈab.laʊt]) is a system of apophony (regular vowel variations) in the Proto-Indo-European language (PIE).
[src:english-language/ablaut] An example of ablaut in English is the strong verb *s**i**ng, s**a**ng, s**u**ng* and its related noun *s**o**ng*, a paradigm inherited directly from the Proto-Indo-European stage of the language.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Traces of ablaut are found in all modern Indo-European languages, though its prevalence varies greatly.
[src:english-language/ablaut] In the context of European languages, the phenomenon was first described in the early 18th century by the Dutch linguist Lambert ten Kate, in his book *Gemeenschap tussen de Gottische spraeke en de Nederduytsche* ("Common aspects of the Gothic and Dutch languages", 1710).
[src:english-language/ablaut] The term *ablaut* is borrowed from German, and derives from the noun *Laut* "sound", and the prefix *ab-*, which indicates movement downwards or away, or deviation from a norm; thus the literal meaning is "sound derivation".
[src:english-language/ablaut] It was coined in this sense in 1819 by the German linguist Jacob Grimm in his *Deutsche Grammatik*, though the word had been used before him.
[src:english-language/ablaut] In particular, the 17th-century grammarian Schottelius had used the word negatively to suggest that German verbs lacked the sophistication of the classics, but there is no hint of this disdain in Grimm or in modern scholarly usage.
[src:english-language/ablaut] In English, the term became established through the 1845 translation of Bopp's *Comparative Grammar*.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Vowel gradation is any vowel difference between two related words (such as *ph**o**tograph* [ˈf**oʊ**təgrɑːf] and *ph**o**tography* [f**ə**ˈtɒgrəfi]) or two forms of the same word (such as *m**a**n* and *m**e**n*).
[src:english-language/ablaut] The difference does not need to be indicated in the spelling.
[src:english-language/ablaut] There are many kinds of vowel gradation in English and other languages, which are discussed generally in the article apophony.
[src:english-language/ablaut] For the study of European languages, one of the most important instances of vowel gradation is the Indo-European ablaut, remnants of which can be seen in the English verbs *r**i**de*, *r**o**de*, *r**i**dden*, or *fl**y***, *fl**ew***, *fl**ow**n*.
[src:english-language/ablaut] In Proto-Indo-European the basic, inherent vowel of most syllables was a short *e*.
[src:english-language/ablaut] *Ablaut* is the name of the process whereby this short *e* changed, becoming short *o*, long *ē*, long *ō*, or sometimes disappearing entirely to leave no vowel at all.
[src:english-language/ablaut] If a syllable had a short *e*, it is said to be in the "e-grade" or "full grade".
[src:english-language/ablaut] When it had no vowel, it is said to be in the "zero grade".
[src:english-language/ablaut] Syllables with long vowels are said to be in "lengthened grade".
[src:english-language/ablaut] A classic example of the five grades of ablaut in a single root is provided by the different case forms of two closely related Greek words.
[src:english-language/ablaut] In the following table, an acute accent (´) marks the syllable carrying the word stress, a macron (¯) marks long vowels, and the syllable in **bold** is the one illustrating the different vowel gradations.
[src:english-language/ablaut] As with most reconstructions, however, scholars differ about the details of this example.
[src:english-language/ablaut] One way to think of this system is to suppose that Proto-Indo-European originally had only one vowel, short *e*, and over time it changed according to phonetic context.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Thus, the language started to develop a more complex vowel system.
[src:english-language/ablaut] It has often been speculated that an original e-grade underwent two changes in some phonetic environments: under certain circumstances, it changed to *o* (the o-grade) and in others, it disappeared entirely (the zero-grade).
[src:english-language/ablaut] However, that is not certain: the phonetic conditions that controlled ablaut have never been determined, and the position of the word stress may not have been a key factor at all.
[src:english-language/ablaut] There are many counterexamples to the proposed rules: **deywós* and its nominative plural **deywóes* show pretonic and posttonic e-grade, respectively, and **wĺ̥kʷos* has an accented zero grade.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Many examples of lengthened grades, including those listed above, are not directly conditioned by ablaut.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Instead, they are a result of sound changes like Szemerényi's law and Stang's law, which caused compensatory lengthening of originally short vowels.
[src:english-language/ablaut] In the examples above, Szemerényi's law affected the older sequences **ph₂-tér-s* and **n̥-péh₂-tor-s*, changing them to **ph₂-tḗr* and **n̥-péh₂-tōr*.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Thus, these forms were originally in the regular, unlengthened e-grade and o-grade.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Such lengthened vowels were, however, later grammaticalised and spread to other words in which the change did not occur.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Nevertheless, there are examples of true lengthened grades, in which short *e* alternates with long *ē*.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Examples are the verbs with "Narten" inflection, and nouns like **mḗh₁-n̥s* "moon", genitive **méh₁-n̥s-os*.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Alternations of this type were rare, however, and the *e* ~ *o* ~ *∅* alternation was the most common by far.
[src:english-language/ablaut] The long *ō* grade was rarer still and may not have actually been a part of the ablaut system at all.
[src:english-language/ablaut] The zero grade of *ablaut* may appear difficult for speakers of English.
[src:english-language/ablaut] In the case of **ph₂trés*, which may already have been pronounced something like [pɐtrés], it is not difficult to imagine it as a contraction of an older **ph₂terés*, pronounced perhaps [pɐterés], as this combination of consonants and vowels would be possible in English as well.
[src:english-language/ablaut] In other cases, however, the absence of a vowel strikes the speaker of a modern western European language as unpronounceable.
[src:english-language/ablaut] When *u* and *i* came in postvocalic positions, the result was a diphthong.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Thus, any of these could replace the ablaut vowel when it was reduced to the zero-grade: the pattern CVrC (for example, **bʰergʰ-*) could become CrC (**bʰr̥gʰ-*).
[src:english-language/ablaut] However, not every PIE syllable was capable of forming a zero grade; some consonant structures inhibited it in particular cases, or completely.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Thus, for example, although the preterite plural of a Germanic strong verb (see below) is derived from the zero grade, classes 4 and 5 have instead vowels representing the lengthened e-grade, as the stems of these verbs could not have sustained a zero grade in this position.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Zero grade is said to be from pre-Proto-Indo-European syncope in unaccented syllables, but in some cases the lack of accent does not cause zero grade: **deywó-*, nominative plural **-es* "god".
[src:english-language/ablaut] There does not seem to be a rule governing the unaccented syllables that take zero grade and the ones that take stronger grades.
[src:english-language/ablaut] It is still a matter of debate whether PIE had an original a-vowel at all.
[src:english-language/ablaut] In later PIE, the disappearance of the laryngeal h₂ could leave an a-colouring and this may explain all occurrences of *a* in later PIE.
[src:english-language/ablaut] However, some argue controversially that the e-grade could sometimes be replaced by an a-grade without the influence of a laryngeal, which might help to explain the vowels in class 6 Germanic verbs, for example.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Although PIE had only this one, basically regular, ablaut sequence, the development in the daughter languages is frequently far more complicated, and few reflect the original system as neatly as Greek.
[src:english-language/ablaut] In particular, the zero grade was often subject to modification from changes in the pronunciation of syllabic sonorants.
[src:english-language/ablaut] For example, in Germanic, syllabic sonorants acquired an epenthetic *-u-*, thus converting the original zero grade to a new "u-grade" in many words.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Thus, while ablaut survives in some form in all Indo-European languages, it became progressively less systematic over time.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Ablaut explains vowel differences between related words of the same language.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Ablaut also explains vowel differences between cognates in different languages.
[src:english-language/ablaut] For the English-speaking non-specialist, a good reference work for quick information on IE roots, including the difference of *ablaut* grade behind related lexemes, is Watkins (2000).
[src:english-language/ablaut] In PIE, there were already ablaut differences within the paradigms of verbs and nouns.
[src:english-language/ablaut] These were not the main markers of grammatical form, since the inflection system served this purpose, but they must have been significant secondary markers.
[src:english-language/ablaut] An example of ablaut in the paradigm of the noun in PIE can be found in **pértus*, from which the English words *ford* and (via Latin) *port* are derived (both via the zero-grade stem **pr̥t-*).
[src:english-language/ablaut] An example in a verb is **bʰeydʰ-* "to wait" (cf.
[src:english-language/ablaut] In the daughter languages, these came to be important markers of grammatical distinctions.
[src:english-language/ablaut] The vowel change in the Germanic strong verb, for example, is the direct descendant of that seen in the Indo-European verb paradigm.
[src:english-language/ablaut] It was in this context of Germanic verbs that *ablaut* was first described, and this is still what most people primarily associate with the phenomenon.
[src:english-language/ablaut] A fuller description of *ablaut* operating in English, German and Dutch verbs and of the historical factors governing these can be found at the article Germanic strong verb.
[src:english-language/ablaut] The same phenomenon is displayed in the verb tables of Latin, Ancient Greek and Sanskrit.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Examples of *ablaut* as a grammatical marker in Latin are the vowel changes in the perfect stem of verbs.
[src:english-language/ablaut] Ablaut can often explain apparently random irregularities.
[src:english-language/ablaut] For example, the verb "to be" in Latin has the forms *est* (he is) and *sunt* (they are).
[src:english-language/ablaut] The equivalent forms in German are very similar: *ist* and *sind*.
[src:english-language/ablaut] The same forms were present in Proto-Slavic: *estь and *sǫtь, and developed into e.g.
[src:english-language/ablaut] The difference between singular and plural in these languages is easily explained: the PIE root is **h₁es-*.
[src:english-language/ablaut] In the singular, the stem is stressed, so it remains in the e-grade, and it takes the inflection **-ti*.
[src:english-language/ablaut] In the plural, however, the inflection **-énti* was stressed, causing the stem to reduce to the zero grade: **h₁es-énti* → **h₁s-énti*.
[src:english-language/ablaut] 3. ending-stressed masculine agent nouns (Greek *trokhós* "wheel" < "*runner").
[src:english-language/ablaut] Many examples of lengthened-grade roots in the daughter languages are actually caused by the effect of laryngeals and of Szemerényi's law and Stang's law, which operated within Indo-European times.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The **Association of Southeast Asian Nations** (**ASEAN**) is an intergovernmental forum of all 11 states in Southeast Asia.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] ASEAN primarily focuses on Southeast Asian economic development, peaceful coexistence and adherence to international norms.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] ASEAN operates on the principle of consensus and respecting national sovereignty, meaning that ASEAN as a whole cannot force another member state to change its domestic laws.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] ASEAN has a population of more than 680 million people and a purchasing power parity-adjusted gross domestic product (GDP) of around 6.3% global GDP.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] ASEAN member states represent a diverse set of economies: the least developed countries like Laos, to emerging economies like Vietnam, to developed economies like Singapore.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Many Southeast Asian projects have originated from decentralized initiatives between member states, such as the ASEAN Power Grid, ASEAN Free Trade Area, ASEAN Integrated QR Code Payment System, or the mutual ASEAN visa-free policies.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Every two years, it organizes a sporting event to promote cultural exchange known as SEA Games.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] ASEAN has strong ties with East Asian and South Asian countries.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It has a vested interest in the security of the South China Sea and the greater Indo-Pacific region.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In terms of diplomacy, ASEAN operates on a principle of centrality, meaning that all concerns from other countries or organizations about Southeast Asia should be routed to ASEAN instead of individual states.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] All Southeast Asian countries, many great powers, and international organizations have dedicated diplomatic presence near ASEAN headquarters in Jakarta.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The roots of ASEAN came from the ASEAN Declaration signed by five Southeast Asian countries in 1967.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Originally, ASEAN was founded to contain communism, but gradually ASEAN was reoriented to focus on economic development and prevent foreign interference in Southeast Asia as a whole.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] As ASEAN expanded and admitted other countries, the member states eventually signed a binding ASEAN Charter in 2008.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] As of 2026, ASEAN are currently dealing with many threats, such as the worsening civil war in Myanmar, territorial disputes in the South China Sea and managing U.S.–China tensions.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Nevertheless, it is widely considered to be a successful example of regional collaboration, and its emphasis on *de facto* standards is seen as an opposite to the legal nature of the European Union.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Since around 100 BCE, the Southeast Asian archipelago occupied a central position at the crossroads of the Indian Ocean and the South China Sea trading routes, which stimulated the economy and the influx of ideas.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] This included the introduction of abugida scripts to Southeast Asia as well as the Chinese script to Vietnam.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Besides various indigenous scripts, various abugida Brahmic scripts were widespread in both continental and insular Southeast Asia.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Historically, scripts such as Pallava, Kawi (from ancient Sanskrit script) and Rencong or *Surat Ulu* were used to write Old Malay, until they were replaced by Jawi during Islamic missionary missions in the Malay Archipelago.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Siam served as the buffer state, sandwiched between British Burma and French Indochina, but its kings had to contend with unequal treaties as well as British and French political interference and territorial losses after the Franco-Siamese conflict of 1893 and the Anglo-Siamese Treaty of 1909.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Under European colonisation, Southeast Asian nations were introduced to European religions and technologies, as well as the Latin alphabet.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Defeat of Imperial Japan eventuated in decolonisation movements throughout Southeast Asia, resulting in the independent ASEAN states seen today.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The predecessor of ASEAN was the Association of Southeast Asia (ASA), formed on 31 July 1961 and consisting of Thailand, the Philippines, and Malaya.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] ASEAN itself was created on 8 August 1967, when the foreign ministers of five countries - Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, and Thailand - signed the ASEAN Declaration at Saranrom Palace in Bangkok, negotiated in Lam Thaen Guest House.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] These events also encouraged the earlier formation of the South East Asia Treaty Organization (SEATO), led by the United States, United Kingdom, and Australia, with several Southeast Asian partners in 1954 as an extension of "containment" policy, seeking to create an Eastern version of NATO.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] However, the local member states of ASEAN group achieved greater cohesion in the mid-1970s following a change in the balance of power after the Fall of Saigon and the end of the Vietnam War in April 1975 and the decline of SEATO.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] ASEAN's first summit meeting, held in Bali, Indonesia, in 1976, resulted in an agreement on several industrial projects and the signing of a Treaty of Amity and Cooperation, and a Declaration of Concord.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The end of the Cold War allowed ASEAN countries to exercise greater political independence in the region, and in the 1990s, ASEAN emerged as a leading voice on regional trade and security issues.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] On 15 December 1995, the Southeast Asian Nuclear-Weapon-Free Zone Treaty was signed to turn Southeast Asia into a nuclear-weapon-free zone.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The treaty took effect on 28 March 1997 after all but one of the member states had ratified it.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It became fully effective on 21 June 2001 after the Philippines ratified it, effectively banning all nuclear weapons in the region.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] On 7 January 1984, Brunei became ASEAN's sixth member and on 28 July 1995, following the end of the Cold War, Vietnam joined as the seventh member.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Laos and Myanmar (formerly Burma) joined two years later on 23 July 1997.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Cambodia was to join at the same time as Laos and Myanmar, but a Cambodian coup in 1997 and other internal instability delayed its entry.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It then joined on 30 April 1999 following the stabilisation of its government.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Timor-Leste joined ASEAN on 26 October 2025 during the 47th ASEAN Summit as its 11th member, it is the latest country to join this association, completing a two-decade accession process.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In 2006, ASEAN was given observer status at the United Nations General Assembly.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In response, the organisation awarded the status of "dialogue partner" to the UN.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The UK and ASEAN have also pursued a dialogue partnership.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] On 15 December 2008, the member states met in Jakarta to launch the charter signed in November 2007, to move closer to "an EU-style community".
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The charter formally established ASEAN as a legal entity, aiming to create a single trade bloc for a region encompassing 500 million people.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Indonesian president Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono stated: "This is a momentous development when ASEAN is consolidating, integrating, and transforming itself into a community.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It is achieved while ASEAN seeks a more vigorous role in Asian and global affairs at a time when the international system is experiencing a seismic shift".
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Referring to climate change and economic upheaval, he concluded: "Southeast Asia is no longer the bitterly divided, war-torn region it was in the 1960s and 1970s".
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The 2008 financial crisis was seen as a threat to the charter's goals, and also set forth the idea of a proposed human rights body to be discussed at a future summit in February 2009.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] This proposition caused controversy, although the body would not have the power to impose sanctions or punish countries which violated citizens' rights and would, therefore, be limited in effectiveness.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The body was established later in 2009 as the ASEAN Intergovernmental Commission on Human Rights (AICHR).
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In November 2012, the commission adopted the ASEAN Human Rights Declaration.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] However, their human rights declaration has been critiqued widely by the international community, with the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights stating that the declaration was worded in problematic ways that do not easily align with international norms.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Likewise, the Human Rights Watch in the United States of America noted several important fundamental rights were omitted or not clearly established.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The chairmanship of ASEAN rotates among the member states.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The Philippines holds the position for 2026.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In response to pandemics, ASEAN has coordinated with ASEAN+3 and other actors to create a regional public health response.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] During the 2002–2004 SARS outbreak, ASEAN and ASEAN+3 worked together to devise a response to the outbreak.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Immediate and short-to-medium term measures were devised.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The parties agreed to enhance sharing of best practices against the disease while also agreeing to bolster collaboration between their respective health authorities and harmonise travel procedures to ensure that proper health screening would occur.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In addition, China offered to contribute $1.2 million to the ASEAN SARS fund, made both to show that it was willing to cooperate with the rest of the region and make amends for its withholding of information during the initial stages of the outbreak.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] ASEAN held a special meeting between ASEAN and ASEAN+3 health ministers on 8 May 2009, on responding to the H1N1 pandemic.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] At this meeting, it was agreed that hotlines would be established between public health authorities, joint response teams would be formed, and oaseangoing research efforts would be bolstered.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Widespread protests and resistance erupted, and elements of the civilian leadership formed an underground "National Unity Government" (NUG).
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Global opposition to the coup emerged, and global pressure was brought on ASEAN to take action.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The 2026 ASEAN summit held in the Philippines, East Timor's Catholic ally, was the first ASEAN summit wherein East Timor participated as a full member of ASEAN.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] This occurred simultaneously with the chairmanship of António Guterres who is the reigning Secretary-General of the United Nations and is of Portuguese and East Timorese ancestry.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Topics discussed in the summit include; socio-economic issues, transportation, utilities, geopolitics, and resilience against crises, and so much more.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] There is currently one state seeking accession to ASEAN: Papua New Guinea.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] There are two states seeking for observer status in ASEAN; Fiji and Bangladesh.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] There was also one state that had formally pursued accession to ASEAN but later stopped, which was Sri Lanka.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The *ASEAN Way* refers to a methodology or approach to solving issues that respect Southeast Asia's cultural norms.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It has been said that the merits of the ASEAN Way might "be usefully applied to global conflict management".
[src:english-language/asean-p01] However, critics have argued that such an approach can be only applied to Asian countries, to specific cultural norms and understandings notably, due to a difference in mindset and level of tension.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Critics object, claiming that the ASEAN Way's emphasis on consultation, consensus, and non-interference forces the organisation to adopt only those policies which satisfy the lowest common denominator.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Decision-making by consensus requires members to see eye-to-eye before ASEAN can move forward on an issue.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Members may not have a common conception of the meaning of the ASEAN Way.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Myanmar, Cambodia, and Laos emphasise non-interference while older member countries focus on co-operation and co-ordination.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] These differences hinder efforts to find common solutions to particular issues, but also make it difficult to determine when collective action is appropriate in a given situation.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Beginning in 1997, heads of each member state adopted the ASEAN Vision 2020 during the group's 30th anniversary meeting held in Kuala Lumpur.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] As a means for the realisation of a single ASEAN community, this vision provides provisions on peace and stability, a nuclear-free region, closer economic integration, human development, sustainable development, cultural heritage, being a drug-free region, environment among others.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The vision also aimed to "see an outward-looking ASEAN playing a pivotal role in the international fora, and advancing ASEAN's common interests".
[src:english-language/asean-p01] ASEAN Vision 2020 was formalised and made comprehensive through the Bali Concord II in 2003.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] To fully embody the three pillars as part of the 2015 integration, blueprints for APSC and ASCC were subsequently adopted in 2009 in Cha-am, Thailand.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The ASEAN Community, initially planned to commence by 2020, was accelerated to begin by 31 December 2015.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It was decided during the 12th ASEAN Summit in Cebu in 2007.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] During the 14th ASEAN Summit, the group adopted the APSC Blueprint.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] This document is aimed at creating a robust political-security environment within ASEAN, with programs and activities outlined to establish the APSC by 2016.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It is based on the ASEAN Charter, the ASEAN Security Community Plan of Action, and the Vientiane Action Program.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The APSC aims to create a sense of responsibility toward comprehensive security and a dynamic, outward-looking region in an increasingly integrated and interdependent world.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The ASEAN Defense Industry Collaboration (ADIC) was proposed at the 4th ASEAN Defense Ministers' Meeting (ADMM) on 11 May 2010 in Hanoi.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Its purpose, among others, is to reduce defence imports from non-ASEAN countries by half and to further develop the defence industry in the region.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It was formally adopted on the next ADMM on 19 May 2011, in Jakarta, Indonesia.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The main focus is to industrially and technologically boost the security capability of ASEAN, consistent with the principles of flexibility and non-binding and voluntary participation among the member states.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The concept revolves around education and capability-building programs to develop the skills and capabilities of the workforce, production of capital for defence products, and the provision of numerous services to address the security needs of each member state.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It also aims to develop an intra-ASEAN defence trade.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] ADIC aims to establish a strong defence industry relying on the local capabilities of each member state and limit annual procurement from external original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Countries like the US, Germany, Russia, France, Italy, UK, China, South Korea, Israel, and the Netherlands are among the major suppliers to ASEAN.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] ASEAN defence budget rose by 147% from 2004 to 2013 and is expected to rise further in the future.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Factors affecting the increase include economic growth, ageing equipment, and the plan to strengthen the establishment of the defence industry.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] ASEANAPOL is also established to enhance cooperation on law enforcement and crime control among police forces of member states.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The AEC aims to "implement economic integration initiatives" to create a single market for member states.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The blueprint that serves as a comprehensive guide for the establishment of the community was adopted on 20 November 2007 at the 13th ASEAN Summit in Singapore.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Its characteristics include a single market and production base, a highly competitive economic region, a region of fair economic development, and a region fully integrated into the global economy.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The areas of cooperation include human resources development, recognition of professional qualifications, closer consultation economic policies, enhanced infrastructure and communications connectivity, integrating industries for regional sourcing, and strengthening private sector involvement.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Through the free movement of skilled labour, goods, services and investment, ASEAN would rise globally as one market, thus increasing its competitiveness and opportunities for development.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] To track the progress of the AEC, a compliance tool called the AEC Scorecard was developed based on the EU Internal Market Scorecard.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It is the only one in effect and is expected to serve as an unbiased assessment tool to measure the extent of integration and the economic health of the region.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It is expected to provide relevant information about regional priorities, and thus foster productive, inclusive, and sustainable growth.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It makes it possible to monitor the implementation of ASEAN agreements, and the achievement of milestones indicated in the AEC Strategic Schedule.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The scorecard outlines specific actions that must be undertaken collectively and individually to establish AEC by 2015.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] To date, two official scorecards have been published, one in 2010, and the other in 2012.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] However, the scorecard is purely quantitative, as it only examines whether a member state has performed the AEC task or not.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The more "yes" answers, the higher the score.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Part of the work towards the ASEAN Economic Community is the integration of the energy systems of the ASEAN member states.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The blueprint for this integration is provided by the ASEAN Plan of Action for Energy Cooperation (APAEC).
[src:english-language/asean-p01] APAEC is managed by the ASEAN Center for Energy.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The realisation of the ASEAN Power Grid (APG) is an important part of APAEC and ASEAN energy cooperation more broadly.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] As trade is liberalised with the integration in 2015, the need arises for ASEAN banking institutions to accommodate and expand their services to an intra-ASEAN market.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Experts, however, have already forecast a shaky economic transition, especially for smaller players in the banking and financial services industry.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Two separate reports by Standard & Poor's (S&P) outline the challenges that ASEAN financial institutions face as they prepare for the 2020 banking integration.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The reports point out that overcrowded banking sector in the Philippines is expected to feel the most pressure as the integration welcomes tighter competition with bigger and more established foreign banks.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] As a result, there needs to be a regional expansion by countries with a small banking sector to lessen the impact of the post-integration environment.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In a follow-up report, S&P recently cited the Philippines for "shoring up its network bases and building up capital ahead of the banking integration – playing defense and strengthening their domestic networks".
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The roadmap for financial integration is the latest regional initiative that aims to strengthen local self-help and support mechanisms.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The roadmap's implementation would contribute to the realisation of the AEC.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Adoption of a common currency, when conditions are ripe, could be the final stage of the AEC.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The roadmap identifies approaches and milestones in capital market development, capital account and financial services liberalisation, and ASEAN currency cooperation.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Capital market development entails promoting institutional capacity as well as the facilitation of greater cross-border collaboration, linkages, and harmonisation between capital markets.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Orderly capital account liberalisation would be promoted with adequate safeguards against volatility and systemic risks.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] To expedite the process of financial services liberalisation, ASEAN has agreed on a positive list modality and adopted milestones to facilitate negotiations.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Member states recognise the importance of strengthening food security to maintain stability and prosperity in the region.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] As ASEAN moves towards AEC and beyond, food security would be an integral part of the community-building agenda.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Strengthened food security is even more relevant in light of potentially severe risks from climate change with agriculture and fisheries being the most affected industries.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Part of the aim of ASEAN integration is to achieve food security collectively via trade in rice and maize.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Trade facilitation measures and the harmonisation/equivalency of food regulation and control standards would reduce the cost of trade in food products.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] While specialisation and revealed comparative and competitive indices point to complementarities between trade patterns among the member states, intra-ASEAN trade in agriculture is quite small, something that integration could address.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The MARKET project would provide flexible and demand-driven support to the ASEAN Secretariat while bringing more private-sector and civil-society input into regional agriculture policy dialogue.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] By building an environment that reduces barriers to trade, ASEAN trade would increase, thereby decreasing the risk of food price crisis.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The ASEAN Socio-Cultural Community (ASCC) was also adopted during the 14th ASEAN Summit.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Its focus areas include human development, social welfare and protection, social justice and rights, environmental sustainability, building the ASEAN identity, and narrowing the development gap.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The group sought economic integration by creating the AEC by the end of 2015 that established a single market.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The average economic growth of member states from 1989 to 2009 was between 3.8% and 7%.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] This was greater than the average growth of APEC, which was 2.8%.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA), established on 28 January 1992, includes a Common Effective Preferential Tariff (CEPT) to promote the free flow of goods between member states.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] ASEAN had only six members when it was signed.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The new member states (Vietnam, Laos, Myanmar, and Cambodia) have not fully met AFTA's obligations, but are officially considered part of the agreement as they were required to sign it upon entry into ASEAN, and were given longer time frames to meet AFTA's tariff reduction obligations.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The next steps are to create a single market and production base, a competitive economic region, a region of equitable economic development, and a region that is fully integrated into the global economy.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Since 2007, ASEAN countries have gradually lowered their import duties to member states, with a target of zero import duties by 2016.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] ASEAN countries have many economic zones (industrial parks, eco-industrial parks, special economic zones, technology parks, and innovation districts) (see reference for comprehensive list from 2015).
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In 2018, eight of the ASEAN members are among the world's outperforming economies, with positive long-term prospect for the region.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] ASEAN's Secretariat projects that the regional body will grow to become the world's fourth largest economy by 2030.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The ASEAN Centre for Energy publishes the ASEAN Energy Outlook every five years, analysing and promoting the integration of national energy systems across the region.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The sixth edition was published in 2020.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] ASEAN planned to establish a single market based upon the four freedoms by the end of 2015, with the goal of ensuring free flow of goods, services, skilled labour, and capital.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The ASEAN Economic Community (AEC) was formed in 2015, but the group deferred about 20% of the harmonisation provisions needed to create a common market and set a new deadline of 2025.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In May 2025, ASEAN adopted a new Community Vision 2045 and AEC Strategic Plan 2026–2030, maintaining a single market as a goal.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Until the end of 2010, intra-ASEAN trade was still low as trade involved mainly exports to countries outside the region, with the exception of Laos and Myanmar, whose foreign trade was ASEAN-oriented.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In 2009, realised foreign direct investment (FDI) was US$37.9 billion and increased two-fold in 2010 to US$75.8 billion.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] 22% of FDI came from the European Union, followed by ASEAN countries (16%), and by Japan and the United States.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The ASEAN Framework Agreement on Trade in Services (AFAS) was adopted at the ASEAN Summit in Bangkok in December 1995.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Under the agreement, member states enter into successive rounds of negotiations to liberalise trade in services with the aim of submitting increasingly higher levels of commitment.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] ASEAN has concluded seven packages of commitments under AFAS.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Mutual Recognition Agreements (MRAs) have been agreed upon by ASEAN for eight professions: physicians, dentists, nurses, architects, engineers, accountants, surveyors, and tourism professionals.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Individuals in these professions will be free to work in any ASEAN states effective 31 December 2015.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In addition, six member states (Malaysia, Vietnam (2 exchanges), Indonesia, Philippines, Thailand, and Singapore) have collaborated on integrating their stock exchanges, which includes 70% of its transaction values with the goal to compete with international exchanges.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Single market will also include the ASEAN Single Aviation Market (ASEAN-SAM), the region's aviation policy geared towards the development of a unified and single aviation market in Southeast Asia.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It was proposed by the ASEAN Air Transport Working Group, supported by the ASEAN Senior Transport Officials Meeting, and endorsed by the ASEAN Transport Ministers.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It is expected to liberalise air travel between member states allowing ASEAN airlines to benefit directly from the growth in air travel, and also free up tourism, trade, investment, and service flows.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Since 1 December 2008, restrictions on the third and fourth freedoms of the air between capital cities of member states for air passenger services have been removed, while from 1 January 2009, full liberalisation of air freight services in the region took effect.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] On 1 January 2011, full liberalisation on fifth freedom traffic rights between all capital cities took effect.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] This policy supersedes existing unilateral, bilateral, and multilateral air services agreements among member states which are inconsistent with its provisions.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The concept of an Asian Currency Unit (ACU) started in the middle of the 1990s, prior to the 1997 Asian financial crisis.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It is a proposed basket of Asian currencies, similar to the European Currency Unit, which was the precursor of the Euro.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The Asian Development Bank is responsible for exploring the feasibility and construction of the basket.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Since the ACU is being considered as a precursor to a common currency, it points to a dynamic economic outlook of the region.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The overall goal of a common currency is to contribute to the financial stability of a regional economy, including price stability.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It means lower cost of cross-border business through the elimination of currency risk.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Greater flows of intra-trade would put pressure on prices, resulting in cheaper goods and services.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Individuals benefit not only from the lowering of prices, they save by not having to change money when travelling, by being able to compare prices more readily, and by the reduced cost of transferring money across borders.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] However, there are conditions for a common currency: the intensity of intra-regional trade and the convergence of macroeconomic conditions.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Substantial intra-ASEAN trade (which is growing, partly as a result of the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) and the ASEAN Economic Community.) and economic integration is an incentive for a monetary union.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Member states currently trade more with other countries (80%) than among themselves (20%).
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Therefore, their economies are more concerned about currency stability against major international currencies, like the US dollar.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] On macroeconomic conditions, member states have different levels of economic development, capacity, and priorities that translate into different levels of interest and readiness.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Monetary integration, however, implies less control over national monetary and fiscal policy to stimulate the economy.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Therefore, greater convergence in macroeconomic conditions is being enacted to improve conditions and confidence in a common currency.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Other concerns include weaknesses in the financial sectors, inadequacy of regional-level resource pooling mechanisms and institutions required to form and manage a currency union, and lack of political preconditions for monetary co-operation and a common currency.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In 1992, the Common Effective Preferential Tariff (CEPT) scheme was adopted as a schedule for phasing out tariffs to increase the "region's competitive advantage as a production base geared for the world market".
[src:english-language/asean-p01] This law would act as the framework for the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA), which is an agreement by member states concerning local manufacturing in ASEAN.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It was signed on 28 January 1992 in Singapore.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Free trade initiatives in ASEAN are spearheaded by the implementation of the ASEAN Trade in Goods Agreement (ATIGA) and the Agreement on Customs.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] These agreements are supported by several sector bodies to plan and to execute free trade measures, guided by the provisions and the requirements of ATIGA and the Agreement on Customs.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] They form a backbone for achieving targets of the AEC Blueprint and establishing the ASEAN Economic Community by the end of 2015.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] On 26 August 2007, ASEAN stated its aim of completing free trade agreements (FTA) with Japan, South Korea, India, Australia, New Zealand, and China by 2013, which is in line with the start of the ASEAN Economic Community by 2015.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In November 2007, ASEAN states signed the ASEAN Charter, a constitution governing relations among member states and establishing the group itself as an international legal entity.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] During the same year, the Cebu Declaration on East Asian Energy Security was signed by ASEAN and the other members of the EAS (Australia, India, Japan, New Zealand, South Korea, China), which pursues energy security by finding energy alternatives to fossil fuels.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] On 27 February 2009, an FTA with Australia and New Zealand was signed.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It is believed that this FTA would boost combined GDP across the 12 countries by more than US$48 billion over the period between 2000 and 2020.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The agreement with Taiwan created the ASEAN–Taiwan Free Trade Area (ACFTA), which went into full effect on 1 January 2010.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In addition, ASEAN was noted to be negotiating an FTA with the European Union.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Bilateral trade with India crossed the US$70 billion target in 2012 (target was to reach the level by 2015).
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Taiwan has also expressed interest in an agreement with ASEAN but needs to overcome diplomatic objections from China.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In 2019, Reuters highlighted a mechanism used by traders to avoid the 70% tariff on ethanol imported into Taiwan from the United States, involving importing the fuel into Malaysia, mixing it with at least 40% ASEAN-produced fuel, and re-exporting it to China tariff-free under ACFTA rules.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Cross-border electricity trade in ASEAN has been limited, despite efforts since 1997 to establish an ASEAN Power Grid and associated trade.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Electricity trade accounts for only about 5% of the generation, whereas trades in coal and gas are 86% and 53% respectively.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] With the institutionalisation of visa-free travel between ASEAN member states, intra-ASEAN travel has escalated.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In 2010, 47% or 34 million out of 73 million tourists in ASEAN member-states were from other ASEAN countries.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Cooperation in tourism was formalised in 1976, following the formation of the Sub-Committee on Tourism (SCOT) under the ASEAN Committee on Trade and Tourism.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The 1st **ASEAN Tourism Forum** was held on 18–26 October 1981 in Kuala Lumpur.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In 1986, ASEAN Promotional Chapters for Tourism (APCT) were established in Hong Kong, West Germany, the United Kingdom, Australia/New Zealand, Japan, and North America.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Tourism has been one of the key growth sectors in ASEAN and has proven resilient amid global economic challenges.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The wide array of tourist attractions across the region drew 109 million tourists to ASEAN in 2015, up by 34% compared to 81 million tourists in 2011.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] As of 2012, tourism was estimated to account for 4.6% of ASEAN GDP—10.9% when taking into account all indirect contributions.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It directly employed 9.3 million people, or 3.2% of total employment, and indirectly supported some 25 million jobs.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In addition, the sector accounted for an estimated 8% of total capital investment in the region.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In January 2012, ASEAN tourism ministers called for the development of a marketing strategy.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The strategy represents the consensus of ASEAN National Tourism Organisations (NTOs) on marketing directions for ASEAN moving forward to 2015.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] 1981 The ASEAN Tourism Forum (ATF) was established.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It is a regional meeting of NGOs, Ministers, sellers, buyers and journalists to promote the ASEAN countries as a single one tourist destination.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The annual event 2019 in Ha Long marks the 38th anniversary and involves all the tourism industry sectors of the 11 member states of ASEAN: Brunei Darussalam, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, Timor-Leste and Vietnam.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] It was organised by TTG Events from Singapore.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The establishment of the China-ASEAN Investment Cooperation Fund was announced in 2009 by Chinese Premier Wen Jiabao began operations in 2010.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The fund, which is sponsored by the Export-Import Bank of China, among other institutional investors, became the first Southeast Asia-focused private equity fund approved by China's State Council and the National Development and Reform Commission.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The Export-Import Bank of China is the "anchor sponsor" with a "seed investment" of US$300 million.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] Three other Chinese institutions invested a combined US$500 million.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] The International Finance Corporation of the World Bank invested US$100 million.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] In November 2011, the China-ASEAN Maritime Cooperation fund was established.
[src:english-language/asean-p01] China underwrote the fund, which is valued at RMB 3 billion.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN maintains a global network of alliances, dialogue partners and diplomatic missions, and is involved in numerous international affairs.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The organisation maintains good relationships on an international scale, particularly towards Asia-Pacific nations, and upholds itself as a neutral party in politics.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] It holds ASEAN Summits, where heads of government of each member states meet to discuss and resolve regional issues, as well as to conduct other meetings with countries outside the bloc to promote external relations and deal with international affairs.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The first summit was held in Bali in 1976.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The third summit was in Manila in 1987, and during this meeting, it was decided that the leaders would meet every five years.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The fourth meeting was held in Singapore in 1992 where the leaders decided to meet more frequently, every three years.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] In 2001, it was decided that the organisation will meet annually to address urgent issues affecting the region.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] In December 2008, the ASEAN Charter came into force and with it, the ASEAN Summit will be held twice a year.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The formal summit meets for three days, and usually includes internal organisation meeting, a conference with foreign ministers of the ASEAN Regional Forum, an ASEAN Plus Three meeting and ASEAN-CER, a meeting of member states with Australia and New Zealand.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN is a major partner of the Shanghai Cooperation Organisation, developing cooperation model with the organisation in the field of security, economy, finance, tourism, culture, environmental protection, development and sustainability.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] It is also the linchpin in the foreign policy of Australia and New Zealand, with the three sides being integrated into an essential alliance.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN also participates in the East Asia Summit (EAS), a pan-Asian forum held annually by the leaders of eighteen countries in the East Asian region, with ASEAN in a leadership position.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Initially, membership included all member states of ASEAN plus China, Japan, South Korea, India, Australia, and New Zealand, but was expanded to include the United States and Russia at the Sixth EAS in 2011, as they were also important players having dominance and influence over the region.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The first summit was held in Kuala Lumpur on 14 December 2005, and subsequent meetings have been held after the annual ASEAN Leaders' Meeting.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The summit has discussed issues including trade, energy, and security and the summit has a role in regional community building.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Other meetings include the ASEAN Ministerial Meeting that focus mostly on specific topics, such as defence or the environment, and are attended by ministers.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF), which met for the first time in 1994, fosters dialogue and consultation, and to promote confidence-building and preventive diplomacy in the region.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] As of July 2007, it consists of twenty-seven participants that include all ASEAN member states, Australia, Bangladesh, Canada, China, the EU, India, Japan, North and South Korea, Mongolia, New Zealand, Pakistan, Papua New Guinea, Russia, Timor-Leste, the United States, and Sri Lanka.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Taiwan has been excluded since the establishment of the ARF, and issues regarding the Taiwan Strait are neither discussed at ARF meetings nor stated in the ARF Chairman's Statements.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN also holds meetings with Europe during the Asia–Europe Meeting (ASEM), an informal dialogue process initiated in 1996 with the intention of strengthening co-operation between the countries of Europe and Asia, especially members of the European Union and ASEAN in particular.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN, represented by its secretariat, is one of the forty-five ASEM partners.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] It also appoints a representative to sit on the governing board of Asia-Europe Foundation (ASEF), a socio-cultural organisation associated with the meeting.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Annual bilateral meetings between ASEAN and India, Russia and the United States are also held.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Prior to 2012, ASEAN foreign ministerial statements were not typically contentious.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Particularly as international disagreements over the South China Sea increased, the wording of ASEAN foreign ministerial statements became more politically contended.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Following the 2022 visit by United States Speaker of the House Nancy Pelosi to Taiwan, ASEAN and individual member states reiterated their support of the One China policy.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] On 12 November 2022, Ukrainian Foreign Minister Dmytro Kuleba urged ASEAN countries to abandon their neutrality and condemn Russia's invasion of Ukraine.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Beyond the Russo-Ukrainian war, the Iran war has also influenced regional alignments.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] According to the ISEAS-Yusof Ishak Institute's State of Southeast Asia 2026 survey, published in April 2026, 52% of Southeast Asian respondents favored alignment with China over the United States amid the Iran war, compared to 48% who still preferred the US.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The survey showed particularly strong preferences for China in Indonesia (80%), Malaysia (68%), and Singapore (66%), while only 23% of Filipino respondents favored China.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Shortly after the conclusion of the South China Sea Arbitration, at the 24 July 2016 China-ASEAN Foreign Ministers summit, China assured ASEAN that it would not conduct land reclamation on the Scarborough Shoal.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The joint statement at the conclusion of the summit emphasised the implementation of the Declaration on the Conduct of Parties in the South China Sea and urged the parties to refrain from inhabiting currently unoccupied islands, reefs, shoals, cays, and other features.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Within ASEAN, Cambodia is often supportive of the PRC's positions, including on the South China Sea issue.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] There have been territorial disputes between ASEAN member states such as the Cambodian–Thai border dispute between Cambodia and Thailand, Cambodian–Vietnamese border dispute between Cambodia and Vietnam, and the North Borneo dispute between the Philippines and Malaysia.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The Vietnamese invasion of Cambodia in 1978, backed by the Soviet Union, was not accepted by ASEAN.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] They rejected it as a violation of the principles of regional integration.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN cooperated with US and Australia to oppose Vietnam's move and it sponsored a Cambodian resolution in the United Nations General Assembly.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN played a major role starting in 1980 in the peace process, leading to the 1991 Paris Agreement.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] In 1990, Malaysia proposed the creation of an East Asia Economic Caucus composed of the members of ASEAN, China, Japan, and South Korea.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] It intended to counterbalance the growing US influence in Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) and Asia as a whole.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] However, the proposal failed because of strong opposition from the US and Japan.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Work for further integration continued, and the ASEAN Plus Three, consisting of ASEAN, China, Japan, and South Korea, was created in 1997.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN Plus Three is a forum that functions as a coordinator of co-operation between the ASEAN and the three East Asian nations of China, South Korea, and Japan.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Government leaders, ministers, and senior officials from the eleven members of ASEAN and the three East Asian states consult on an increasing range of issues.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN Plus Three is the latest development of Southeast Asia-East Asia regional co-operation.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] In the past, proposals, such as South Korea's call for an Asian Common Market in 1970 and Japan's 1988 suggestion for an Asian Network, have been made to bring closer regional co-operation.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The first leaders' meetings were held in 1996, and 1997 to deal with Asia–Europe Meeting issues, and China and Japan each wanted regular summit meetings with ASEAN members afterwards.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The group's significance and importance were strengthened by the 1997 Asian financial crisis.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] In response to the crisis, ASEAN closely cooperated with China, South Korea, and Japan.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Since the implementation of the Joint Statement on East Asia Cooperation in 1999 at the Manila Summit, ASEAN Plus Three finance ministers have been holding periodic consultations.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN Plus Three, in establishing the Chiang Mai Initiative, has been credited as forming the basis for financial stability in Asia, the lack of such stability having contributed to the 1997 Asian financial crisis.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] With the aim of further strengthening the nations' co-operation, East Asia Vision Group (EAVG) II was established at the 13th ASEAN Plus Three Summit on 29 October 2010 in Hanoi to stock-take, review, and identify the future direction of the co-operation.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The ASEAN Plus Three framework also serves as a platform for the ASEAN affiliated intergovernmental organisations in China, Korea, and Japan to meet and cooperate.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The ASEAN-China Centre, the ASEAN-Japan Centre, and ASEAN-Korea Centre currently convene annually to discuss ongoing projects and to discuss possible areas of cooperation vis-a-vis ASEAN.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN Plus Three was the first of attempts for further integration to improve existing ties of Southeast Asia with East Asian countries of China, Japan and South Korea.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] This was followed by the even larger East Asia Summit (EAS), which included ASEAN Plus Three as well as India, Australia, and New Zealand.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] This group acted as a prerequisite for the planned East Asia Community which was supposedly patterned after the European Community (now transformed into the European Union).
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The ASEAN Eminent Persons Group was created to study this policy's possible successes and failures.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The group became ASEAN Plus Six with Australia, New Zealand, and India, and stands as the linchpin of the Asia–Pacific's economic, political, security, socio-cultural architecture, as well as the global economy.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Codification of the relations between these countries has seen progress through the development of the Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership, a free-trade agreement involving the 15 countries of ASEAN Plus Six (excluding India).
[src:english-language/asean-p02] RCEP would, in part, allow the members to protect local sectors and give more time to comply with the aim for developed country members.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] India temporarily does not join the RCEP for the protection of its own market, but Japan, China, and ASEAN welcomes India's participation.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Taiwan has been excluded from participating with the organisation owing to China's influence on the Asia–Pacific through its economic and diplomatic influence.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] At the turn of the 21st century, ASEAN began to discuss environmental agreements.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] These included the signing of the ASEAN Agreement on Transboundary Haze Pollution in 2002 as an attempt to control haze pollution in Southeast Asia, arguably the region's most high-profile environmental issue.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Unfortunately, this was unsuccessful due to the outbreaks of haze in 2005, 2006, 2009, 2013, and 2015.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Thirteen years after signing the ASEAN Agreement on Transboundary Haze Pollution, the situation with respect to the long term issue of Southeast Asian haze had not changed for 50% of the ASEAN member states, and still remained as a crisis every two years during summer and fall.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Trash dumping from foreign countries (such as Japan and Canada) to ASEAN has yet to be discussed and resolved.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN's aggregate economy is one of the fastest growing in the world.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] It is expected to grow by 4.6% in 2019, and 4.8% in 2020, but at the cost of the release about 1.5 billion tonnes of CO2 to the atmosphere every year.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] That makes ASEAN a greater source of greenhouse gas emissions than Japan (1.3 billion tonnes per year) or Germany (796 million tonnes per year).
[src:english-language/asean-p02] It is the only region in the world where coal is expected to increase its share of the energy mix.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] According to the International Energy Agency (IEA), "Since 2000 [ASEAN's] overall energy demand has grown by more than 80% and the lion's share of this growth has been met by a doubling in fossil fuel use,...
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Oil is the largest element in the regional energy mix and coal, largely for power generation, has been the fastest growing." ASEAN has been criticised for not doing enough to mitigate climate change although it is the world's most vulnerable region in terms of climate impact.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN has many opportunities for renewable energy.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Vietnam's experience in solar and wind power development provides relevant implications for the other ASEAN countries.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The proposed ASEAN Power Grid could allow for renewable energy transmission from large producers like Vietnam to others within ASEAN.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The ASEAN has initiated its transition to cleaner energy sources.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] This transition is characterised as Demanding, Doable, and Dependent.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] With approximately 700 million inhabitants, the region is witnessing a substantial surge in energy demand, projected to triple by 2050.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] However, transitioning energy sources requires significant resources.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Southeast Asia would need to invest US$27 billion annually in renewable energy to achieve the target of 23% renewables in the primary energy supply by 2025.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Nevertheless, this goal is attainable with the implementation of appropriate policies.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Vietnam serves as a compelling example of rapid adoption of solar and wind energy.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Since 2019, Vietnam has emerged as a regional leader, with solar and wind energy accounting for 13% of its electricity mix in 2022, a remarkable increase from nearly zero in 2017.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Though, the region requires international assistance to meet its net-zero emission targets.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Phasing out coal remains a daunting task, although countries such as Indonesia and Vietnam have pledged to phasing out coal power by 2040s.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Several high-profile leaders such as the head of the Indonesian national energy company PLN, Darmawan Prasodjo, have stated that the ASEAN Power Grid proposal is key to unlocking the potential for green energy in southeast Asia.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] At the 11th ASEAN Summit in December 2005, leaders set new direction for regional education collaboration when they welcomed the decision of the ASEAN education ministers to convene meetings on a regular basis.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The annual ASEAN Education Ministers Meeting oversees co-operation efforts on education at the ministerial level.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] With regard to implementation, programs, and activities are carried out by the ASEAN Senior Officials on Education (SOM-ED).
[src:english-language/asean-p02] SOM-ED also manages co-operation on higher education through the ASEAN University Network (AUN).
[src:english-language/asean-p02] It is a consortium of Southeast Asian tertiary institutions of which 30 currently belong as participating universities.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] In November 2011, ten vocational schools and centres were established in China to help develop human resources to assist in the economic and social development of the ASEAN countries.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN also has a scholarship program offered by Singapore to the 9 other member states for secondary school, junior college, and university education.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] It covers accommodation, food, medical benefits and accident insurance, school fees, and examination fees.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Its recipients, who perform well on the GCE Advanced Level Examination, may apply for ASEAN undergraduate scholarships, which are tailored specifically to undergraduate institutions in Singapore and other ASEAN member countries.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] 'Australia for ASEAN' scholarships are also offered by the Australian Government to the 'next generation of leaders' from ASEAN member states.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] By undertaking a Master's degree, recipients are to develop the skills and knowledge to drive change, help build links with Australia, and also participate in the Indo-Pacific Emerging Leaders Program to help develop the ASEAN Outlook for the Indo-Pacific.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Each ASEAN member state is able to receive ten 'Australia for ASEAN' scholarships.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The ASEAN Qualifications Reference Framework is the regional qualifications framework developed by the ASEAN and is used by ASEAN member states to link the various national qualifications framework.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The framework was endorsed by the ASEAN Economic Ministers in August 2014; the ASEAN Education Ministers in September 2014; and the ASEAN Labour Ministers through an Ad-referendum from November 2014 to May 2015.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] In July 2019, the population of the ASEAN was about 655 million people (8.5% of the world population).
[src:english-language/asean-p02] In ASEAN in 2019, 55.2 million people were children age 0–4 and 46.3 million people were older than 65.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] This corresponds to 8.4% and 7.1% of the total ASEAN population.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The region's population growth is 1.1% per year.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Thailand is the lowest at 0.2% per year, and Cambodia is the highest at 1.9% per year.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN's sex ratio is 99.4 males per 100 females, as of 2017.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Just over half (around 50.1%) of Southeast Asia's inhabitants lived in urban areas in 2020, projected to rise to 55.6% in 2030, a total of almost 405 million people.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Urbanisation is concentrated in coastal plains and river deltas, giving the region a dense belt of large cities around the Java Sea, South China Sea and Gulf of Thailand.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Southeast Asia contains dozens of metropolitan areas with populations of over 1 million; ASEAN data indicate that about 13% of the region's citizens live in 28 cities with more than one million inhabitants, with a further 14% in 367 settlements of between 100,000 and 1 million people.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] With a population of roughly 42 million in 2025, Greater Jakarta (Jabodetabek) is the largest metropolitan area in Southeast Asia and one of the largest urban agglomerations in the world, followed by the Greater Manila Area with about 28 million inhabitants.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Jakarta and Manila, together with Bangkok, form the three largest metropolitan areas in Southeast Asia and are widely classed as megacities with metropolitan populations exceeding ten million.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] They are followed by major metropolitan regions centred on Ho Chi Minh City, Singapore, Kuala Lumpur, Hanoi, Surabaya and other large cities across Indonesia, the Philippines, Thailand, Vietnam and Malaysia.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The organisation hosts cultural activities in an attempt to further integrate the region.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] These include sports and educational activities as well as writing awards.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Examples of these include the ASEAN Centre for Biodiversity, ASEAN Heritage Parks and the ASEAN Outstanding Scientist and Technologist Award.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] In addition, the ASEAN region has been recognised as one of the world's most diverse regions ethnically, religiously and linguistically.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Member states have promoted co-operation in information to help build an ASEAN identity.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] One of the main bodies in ASEAN co-operation in information is the ASEAN Committee on Culture and Information (COCI).
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Established in 1978, its mission is to promote effective co-operation in the fields of information, as well as culture, through its various projects and activities.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] It includes representatives from national institutions like the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Ministries of Culture and Information, national radio and television networks, museums, archives and libraries, among others.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The representatives meet annually to formulate and agree on projects in support of their mission.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] On 14 November 2014, foreign ministers of member states launched the ASEAN Communication Master Plan (ACPM).
[src:english-language/asean-p02] It provides a framework for communicating the character, structure, and overall vision of ASEAN and the ASEAN community to key audiences within the region and globally.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN Media Cooperation (AMC) sets digital television standards and policies in preparation for broadcasters to transition from analogue to digital broadcasting.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] This collaboration was conceptualised during the 11th ASEAN Ministers Responsible for Information (AMRI) Conference in Malaysia on 1 March 2012 where a consensus declared that both new and traditional media were keys to connecting ASEAN peoples and bridging cultural gaps in the region.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Music plays a significant role in ASEAN affairs, as evidenced by the new music composed for, and to be performed at, the 34th ASEAN Summit in Bangkok in June 2019.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The main sporting event of ASEAN is the Southeast Asian Games, a biennial meet of athletes from the eleven member-states.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN has been credited by many as among the world's most influential organisations and a global powerhouse.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The organisation plays a prominent role in regional and international diplomacy, politics, security, economy and trade.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The ASEAN Free Trade Area also stands as one of the largest and most important free trade areas in the world, and together with its network of dialogue partners, drove some of the world's largest multilateral forums and blocs, including APEC, EAS and RCEP.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Critics have charged ASEAN with weakly promoting human rights and democracy, particularly in junta-led Myanmar.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Some scholars think that non-interference has hindered ASEAN efforts to handle the Myanmar issue, human rights abuse, and haze pollution in the area.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Despite global outrage at the military crack-down on unarmed protesters in Yangon, ASEAN has refused to suspend Myanmar as a member and also rejects proposals for economic sanctions.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] This has caused concern as the European Union has refused to conduct free trade negotiations at a regional level for these political reasons.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] During a UN vote against the ethnic cleansing of Rohingya, most member states voted to either abstain or against the condemnation.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Only the Muslim-majority countries Malaysia, Indonesia, and Brunei voted to condemn the cleansing of Rohingya.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Some international observers view ASEAN as a "talk shop", stating that the organisation is: "big on words, but small on action".
[src:english-language/asean-p02] "ASEAN policies have proven to be mostly rhetoric, rather than actual implementation", according to Pokpong Lawansiri, a Bangkok-based independent analyst of ASEAN.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] "It has been noted that less than 50% of ASEAN agreements are actually implemented, while ASEAN holds more than six hundred meetings annually".
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The head of the International Institute of Strategic Studies, Tim Huxley, cites the diverse political systems present in the grouping, including many young states, as a barrier to far-reaching co-operation beyond economics.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] He also asserts that, without an external threat to rally against after the Cold War ended, ASEAN has less successfully restrained its members and resolved such border disputes as those between Myanmar and Thailand or Indonesia and Malaysia.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] During the 12th ASEAN Summit in Cebu, several activist groups staged anti-globalisation protests, arguing that the agenda of economic integration would negatively affect industries in the Philippines and would deprive thousands of Filipinos of their jobs.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Corruption remains a widespread issue, as "tea money" remains an important requirement to grease business transactions and to receive public services.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The group's integration plan has raised concerns, in particular, the 2015 deadline.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Business and economy experts who attended the Lippo-UPH Dialogue in Naypyidaw cited unresolved issues relating to aviation, agriculture, and human resources.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Some panelists, among them, Kishore Mahbubani, warned against high expectations at the onset.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] He stated: "Please do not expect a big bang event in 2015 where everything is going to happen overnight when the ASEAN Economic Community comes into being.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Some panelists enumerated other matters to be dealt with for a successful launch.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Among them were the communications issues involving the 600 million citizens living in the region, increasing understanding in business, current visa arrangements, demand for specific skills, banking connections, and economic differences.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Former Philippine National Statistical Coordination Board (NSCB) Secretary General Romulo A.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Virola, said in 2012 that the Philippines seems unready to benefit from the integration due to its "wobbly" economic performance compared to other member states.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] According to Virola, the Philippines continues to lag behind in terms of employment rate, tourism, life expectancy, and cellular subscriptions.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Nestor Tan, head of BDO Unibank Inc., said that while some businesses see the Asian Economic Blueprint (AEC) as an opportunity, the integration would be more of a threat to local firms.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Tan added that protecting the Philippines' agricultural and financial services sectors, as well as the labour sector, would be necessary for the implementation of AEC by 2015.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Standard & Poor's also believed that banks in the Philippines are not yet prepared for the tougher competition that would result from the integration.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] In one of its latest publications, S&P said banks in the country, although profitable and stable, operate on a much smaller scale than their counterparts in the region.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The US Chamber of Commerce has highlighted widespread concern that the much-anticipated AEC could not be launched by the 2015 deadline.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] In January 2014, former ASEAN Secretary-General Rodolfo C.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] In 2012, the commencement of the AEC was postponed to 31 December 2015 from the original plan of 1 January.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Despite Secretary-General Surin Pitsuwan's firm reassurance that "[t]here will be no more delays and that all ten ASEAN countries will participate", even the most fervent proponents of AEC worried that AEC would not be delivered on time as December 2015 neared.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] An article published by *Vietnam News* echoed some of the challenges and opportunities that Vietnam faces in preparation for the AEC.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The article said that the deputy head of the Ministry of Industry and Trade, Tran Thanh Hai, was concerned about local enterprises' lack of knowledge of the AEC.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] It was said that 80% of local enterprises surveyed acknowledged that they have little information about the interests and challenges available for them in the ASEAN market.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Another challenge is the need to compete with other countries in the ASEAN market to export raw products since the country had mainly exported raw products.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The Asian Development Bank also has doubts about Cambodia's ability to meet the AEC deadline.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The leading economist of ADB, Jayant Menon, said that Cambodia needs to speed up its customs reform and to press ahead with automating processes to reduce trade costs and minimise the opportunities for corruption and be ready for the implementation of its National Single Window by 2015.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Despite an ASEAN Economic Community goal of significant economic integration as laid out in the AEC Blueprint 2025, ASEAN continues to face challenges towards integration.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] A report published by the Asian Trade Centre in 2019 identified multiple sectors that face challenges towards integration due to non-tariff barriers that still exist in the region.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The report stated that the goals of the AEC 2025 would not be accomplished if ASEAN fails to address the issues of non-tariff measures and eliminate non-tariff barriers in the region.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Accordingly, ASEAN has embraced the idea of cooperative security which means that ASEAN's approach to security issues is through confidence-building measures and transparency for reducing the tension and conflict between its members.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Piracy in the strait of Malacca and in the Sulu and Celebes Sea is one of the main non-traditional security threats for the region, it has challenged the capacity of its members to ensure coordination of effective policy actions to reduce this phenomenon.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] In this sense, spread all over the countries of Southeast Asia, criminal organisations with complex structures pose a challenge to ASEAN's coordination capacity to solve the problem despite the plans created within its institutional framework.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Although some measures have been implemented by ASEAN, still the complexity of the problem requires deep solutions of cooperation that might alter the balance of its framework.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Additionally, the APSC promotes "regional peace and stability through abiding respect for justice and the rule of law in the relationship among countries of the region and adherence to the principles of the United Nations Charter".
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Nonetheless, the institutional framework and decision-making procedures in ASEAN make difficult to reach agreements on piracy.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] ASEAN has struggled to deliver a coordinated response to solve this problem in the region mainly by two reasons: the first one, could be related to the focalised nature of the problem in subregions rather than the whole region.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The second one, consensus on non-traditional security issues has been difficult to reach due to contradictory interest between member states, particularly in joint operations between navies and the reach of these joint operations.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] These issues are generated mainly by unresolved territorial disputes, specially in the maritime domain, at some extent they pose a challenge to ASEAN members in their capacity to cooperate in regards to the maritime security approach.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Consequently, a greater multilateral cooperation has been pushed by the members to solve the piracy challenges on economy, trading and security.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Members of the ASEAN, have addressed the necessity for the regional organisation to make some concessions and rearrangements to respond to the challenges that non-traditional security (specifically piracy) issues posse to the security of the ASEAN members.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Despite the efforts and plans made by the ASEAN, this organisation is expected to overcome the image of being regarded solely as a forum to discuss security issues.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Two possible solutions has been proposed by some member states for this purpose: 1.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Promoting relationships with other major actors regionally to overcome the short-time challenges and 2.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Rearrange the institutional framework to "avoid contention and seek cooperation to maximize the aggregate ability in order to benefit from making the sea fulfil its economic, security and other goals".
[src:english-language/asean-p02] In addition to piracy, there are several significant issues facing ASEAN today, including human rights violations, repression, and democratic backsliding.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Across the region, various political leaders are known human rights abusers, however there is no proper accountability process, and often human rights violations are sidelined by economic or political interests.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Myanmar is in the midst of a devastating civil war, during which the military government that was installed following a coup d'état, has carried out human rights violations against the Rohingya population.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Political instability in Thailand, particularly due to recurring military involvement in government, has raised concerns within ASEAN about regional stability.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Since the 2006 coup, Thailand has experienced multiple military interventions in politics, including the 2014 coup led by General Prayuth Chan-ocha, which resulted in nearly a decade of military-backed governance.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Observers note that Thailand's military dominance has complicated ASEAN's ability to respond cohesively to regional challenges.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] Domestic instability has at times influenced its foreign policy stance, affecting negotiations on security cooperation and regional humanitarian crises.
[src:english-language/asean-p02] The navies of ASEAN member countries participate in the different editions of the ASEAN Multilateral Naval Exercise, or AMNEX.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] English is either the official language, or one of the official languages, of 57 sovereign states and 30 dependent territories, making it the most geographically widespread language in the world.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In the United Kingdom, the United States, Australia, and New Zealand, it is the dominant language for historical reasons without being explicitly defined by law.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] It is a co‑official language of the United Nations, the European Union, and many other international and regional organisations.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] It has also become the *de facto* lingua franca of diplomacy, science, technology, international trade, logistics, tourism, aviation, entertainment, and the Internet.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] *Ethnologue* estimated that there were over 1.4 billion speakers worldwide as of 2021.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Old English emerged from a group of West Germanic dialects spoken by the Anglo-Saxons.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Early inscriptions were written with runes before a Latin‑based alphabet was adopted for longer texts.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Late Old English borrowed some grammar and core vocabulary from Old Norse, a North Germanic language.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] An evolution of the Latin alphabet, the English alphabet, fully supplanted the runic alphabet by the High Middle Ages, coinciding with the emergence of Middle English in England under Norman control.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Middle English borrowed vocabulary extensively from French dialects, which are the source of approximately 28 per cent of Modern English words, and from Latin, which is the source of an additional 28 per cent.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] While Latin and the Romance languages are thus the source for a majority of its lexicon taken as a whole, English's grammar and phonology remain Germanic, as does most of its basic everyday vocabulary.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Finally, Middle English transformed, in part through the Great Vowel Shift, into Modern English, which exists on a dialect continuum with Scots; it is next most closely related to Low Saxon and Frisian.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] English is a member of the Indo-European language family, belonging to the West Germanic branch of Germanic languages.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Old English was one of several Ingvaeonic languages, which emerged from a dialect continuum spoken by West Germanic peoples during the 5th century in Frisia, on the coast of the North Sea.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Old English emerged among the Ingvaeonic speakers on the British Isles following their migration to the region, while the other Ingvaeonic languages (Frisian and Old Low German) developed in parallel on the European continent.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Old English evolved into Middle English, which in turn evolved into Modern English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Particular dialects of Old and Middle English also developed into other Anglic languages, including Scots and the extinct Fingallian and Yola dialects of Ireland.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] English was isolated from other Germanic languages on the continent and diverged considerably in vocabulary, syntax, and phonology as a result.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] It is not mutually intelligible with any continental Germanic language – though some, such as Dutch and Frisian, share strong affinities with it, particularly in its earlier stages.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] English and Frisian were traditionally considered more closely related to one another than they were to other West Germanic languages, but most modern scholarship does not recognise a particular affinity between them.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Though they shared similar sound changes that were found nowhere else around the North Sea at that time, the specific changes appeared in English and Frisian at different times – a pattern that is uncharacteristic of languages that share a unique phylogenetic ancestor.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Old English (also called *Anglo-Saxon*) was the earliest form of the English language, spoken from c.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Old English developed from a set of West Germanic dialects, sometimes identified as Anglo-Frisian or North Sea Germanic, originally spoken along the coasts of Frisia, Lower Saxony and southern Jutland by the Germanic peoples known from historical records as the Angles, Saxons, and Jutes.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] From the 5th century, the Anglo-Saxons settled Britain as the Roman economy and administration collapsed.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] By the 7th century, Old English had become dominant in Britain – replacing the Common Brittonic and British Latin previously spoken during the Roman occupation, which left little influence on English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] *England* and *English* (originally *Ænglaland* and *Ænglisc*) are both named after the Angles.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Old English was divided into two Anglian dialects (Mercian and Northumbrian) and two Saxon dialects (Kentish and West Saxon).
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Through the influence of the kingdom of Wessex and the educational reforms instated by King Alfred during the 9th century, the West Saxon dialect became the standard written variety.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The epic poem *Beowulf* is written in West Saxon, and the earliest English poem, *Cædmon's Hymn*, is written in Northumbrian.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Modern English developed mainly from Mercian, but the Scots language developed from Northumbrian.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] During the earliest period of Old English, a few short inscriptions were made using a runic alphabet.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] By the 7th century, a Latin alphabet had been adopted.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Written with half-uncial letterforms, it included the runic letters *wynn* ⟨*ƿ*⟩ and *thorn* ⟨*þ*⟩, and the modified Latin letters *eth* ⟨*ð*⟩ and *ash* ⟨*æ*⟩.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Old English is markedly different from Modern English; 21st‑century English speakers are entirely unable to understand Old English without special training.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Its grammar was similar to that of modern German: nouns, adjectives, pronouns, and verbs had many more inflectional endings and forms, and word order was much freer than in Modern English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Modern English has case forms in pronouns (*he*, *him*, *his*) and a few verb inflections (*speak*, *speaks*, *speaking*, *spoke*, *spoken*), but Old English had case endings in nouns as well, and verbs had more person and number endings.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Between the 8th and 11th centuries, the English spoken in some regions underwent significant changes due to contact with Old Norse, a North Germanic language.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Several waves of Norsemen colonising the northern British Isles in the 8th and 9th centuries brought Old English speakers into constant contact with Old Norse.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Norse influence was strongest in the north‑eastern varieties of Old English spoken in the Danelaw surrounding York; today these features are still particularly evident in Scots and Northern English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The centre of Norse influence was Lindsey, located in the Midlands.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] After Lindsey was incorporated into the Anglo‑Saxon polity in 920, English spread extensively throughout the region.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] One element of Norse influence that persists in all English varieties today is the third‑person pronoun group beginning with *th-* (*they*, *them*, *their*), which replaced the Anglo‑Saxon pronouns with *h-* (*hie, him, hera*).
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Other Norse loanwords include *give*, *get*, *sky*, *skirt*, *egg*, and *cake*, typically displacing a native Anglo‑Saxon equivalent.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Old Norse in this era remained largely mutually intelligible with some dialects of Old English, particularly northern ones.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The Middle English period is often defined as beginning with the Norman Conquest in 1066.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] During the centuries that followed, English was heavily influenced by the form of Old French spoken by the new Norman ruling class that had migrated to England (known as Old Norman).
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Over the following decades of contact, members of the middle and upper classes, whether native English or Norman, became increasingly bilingual.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] By 1150 at the latest, bilingual speakers represented a majority of the English aristocracy, and monolingual French speakers were nearly non‑existent.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The French spoken by the Norman elite in England eventually developed into the Anglo‑Norman language.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The transition from Old to Middle English can also be placed during the composition of the *Ormulum* (c. late 12th century), a work by the Augustinian canon Orrm which highlights the blending of Old English and Anglo‑Norman elements in the language for the first time.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] As the lower classes, who represented the vast majority of the population, remained monolingual English speakers, the primary influence of Norman was as a lexical superstratum, introducing a wide range of loanwords related to politics, legislation, and prestigious social domains.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] For instance, the French word *trône* appears for the first time, from which the English word *throne* is derived.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Middle English also greatly simplified the inflectional system, probably in order to reconcile Old Norse and Old English, which were inflectionally different but morphologically similar.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The distinction between nominative and accusative cases was lost except in personal pronouns; the instrumental case was dropped; and the use of the genitive case was limited to indicating possession.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The inflectional system regularised many irregular inflectional forms, and gradually simplified the system of agreement, making word order less flexible.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Middle English literature includes Geoffrey Chaucer's *Canterbury Tales* (c.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] During the Middle English period, the use of regional dialects in writing proliferated, and dialect traits were even used for effect by authors such as Chaucer.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In the first translation of the entire Bible into English by John Wycliffe (1382), Matthew 8:20 reads: "Foxis han dennes, and briddis of heuene han nestis." Here the plural suffix *-n* on the verb *have* is still retained, but none of the case endings on the nouns are present.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The period of Early Modern English, lasting from 1500 to 1700, was characterised by the Great Vowel Shift (1350–1700), inflectional simplification, and linguistic standardisation.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The Great Vowel Shift affected the stressed long vowels of Middle English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] It was a chain shift, meaning that each shift triggered a subsequent shift in the vowel system.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Mid and open vowels were raised, and close vowels were broken into diphthongs.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] For example, the word *bite* was originally pronounced as the word *beet* is today, and the second vowel in the word *about* was pronounced as the word *boot* is today.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The Great Vowel Shift explains many irregularities in spelling, since English retains many spellings from Middle English, and it also explains why English vowel letters have very different pronunciations from the same letters in other languages.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] English began to rise in prestige relative to Norman French during the reign of Henry V.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Around 1430, the Court of Chancery in Westminster began using English in its official documents, and a new standard form of Middle English, known as Chancery Standard, developed from the dialects of London and the East Midlands.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In 1476, William Caxton introduced the printing press to England and began publishing the first printed books in London, thereby expanding the influence of this form of English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Literature in Early Modern English includes the works of William Shakespeare and the 1611 King James Version (KJV) of the Bible.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Even after the vowel shift, the language still sounded different from Modern English: for example, the consonant clusters /kn ɡn sw/ in *knight*, *gnat*, and *sword* were still pronounced.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Many of the grammatical features that a modern reader of Shakespeare might find quaint or archaic represent the distinct characteristics of Early Modern English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] By the late 18th century, the British Empire had spread English through its colonies and geopolitical dominance.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Commerce, science and technology, diplomacy, art, and formal education all contributed to English becoming the first truly global language.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] English also facilitated worldwide international communication.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] English was adopted in parts of North America, parts of Africa, Oceania, and many other regions.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] When they obtained political independence, some of the newly independent states that had multiple indigenous languages opted to continue using English as the official language, in order to avoid the political and other difficulties inherent in promoting any one indigenous language above the others.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In the 20th century, the growing economic and cultural influence of the United States and its status as a superpower following the Second World War – along with worldwide broadcasting in English by the BBC and other broadcasters – has caused the language to spread across the planet much faster.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In 1951, the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) recommended to the International Chicago Convention that Aviation English be universally adopted for "international aeronautical radiotelephony communications".
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In 2001, the International Maritime Organization (IMO) developed a set of key phrases, named Standard Marine Communication Phrases (SMCP), in English, to be the recognised language supported by the international maritime community for use at sea.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In the 21st century, English is more widely spoken and written than any other language in history.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] As Modern English developed, explicit norms for standard usage were published and spread through official media such as public education and state‑sponsored publications.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In 1755, Samuel Johnson published his *Dictionary of the English Language*, which introduced standard spellings of words and usage norms.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In 1828, Noah Webster published the *American Dictionary of the English Language* to establish a norm for speaking and writing American English independent of the British standard.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Within Britain, non‑standard or lower‑class dialect features were increasingly stigmatised, leading to the rapid spread of the prestige varieties among the middle classes.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In modern English, the loss of grammatical case is almost complete (it is now found only in pronouns, such as *he* and *him*, *she* and *her*, *who* and *whom*), and subject–verb–object word order is largely fixed.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Some changes, such as the use of *do*-support, have become universalised.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] (Earlier English did not use the word *do* as a general auxiliary as Modern English does; at first it was used only in question constructions, and even then it was not obligatory.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Now, *do*-support with the verb *have* is becoming increasingly standardised.) The use of progressive forms ending in *-ing* appears to be spreading to new constructions, and forms such as "had been being built" are becoming more common.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Regularisation of irregular forms also continues slowly (e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] *dreamed* instead of *dreamt*), and analytical alternatives to inflectional forms are becoming more common (e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] British English is also undergoing change under the influence of American English, fuelled by the strong presence of American English in the media.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] As of 2016, 400 million people spoke English as their first language, and 1.1 billion spoke it as a second language.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] English is the largest language by number of speakers, spoken by communities on every continent.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Estimates of second‑language and foreign‑language speakers vary greatly depending on how proficiency is defined, ranging from 470 million to more than 1 billion.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In 2003, David Crystal estimated that non‑native speakers outnumbered native speakers by a ratio of three to one.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Braj Kachru has categorised countries into the Three Circles of English model, according to how the language historically spread in each country, how it is acquired by the population, and the range of uses it has there – with a country's classification being able to change over time.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] 'Inner‑circle' countries have large communities of native English speakers; these include the United Kingdom, the United States, Australia, Canada, Ireland, and New Zealand (where the majority speaks English), as well as South Africa (where a significant minority speaks English).
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The countries with the most native English speakers are, in descending order: the United States (at least 231 million), the United Kingdom (60 million), Canada (19 million), Australia (at least 17 million), South Africa (4.8 million), Ireland (4.2 million), and New Zealand (3.7 million).
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In these countries, children of native speakers learn English from their parents; citizens with other first languages, as well as incoming immigrants, learn English in order to communicate in local English‑speaking neighbourhoods and workplaces.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Inner‑circle countries are the base from which English spreads to other regions of the world.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] These countries have millions of native speakers on dialect continua, which range from English-based creole languages to standard varieties of English used in inner‑circle countries.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] They have many more speakers who acquire English as they grow up through day‑to‑day use and exposure to English‑language broadcasting, especially if they attend schools where English is the language of instruction.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] 'Expanding‑circle' countries are those where English is taught as a foreign language, though the character of English as a first, second, or foreign language in a given country is often debatable and may change over time.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] For example, in countries such as the Netherlands, an overwhelming majority of the population can speak English, and it is often used in higher education and to communicate with foreigners.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] English is a pluricentric language, which means that no single national authority sets the standard for its use.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Spoken English, including English used in broadcasting, generally follows national pronunciation standards that are established by custom rather than by regulation.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] International broadcasters are usually identifiable as coming from one country rather than another through their accents, but newsreader scripts are also composed largely in international standard written English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The norms of standard written English are maintained purely by the consensus of educated English speakers around the world, without any oversight by any government or international organisation.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] American listeners readily understand most British broadcasting, and British listeners readily understand most American broadcasting.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Most English speakers around the world can understand radio programmes, television programmes, and films from many parts of the English-speaking world.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Both standard and non‑standard varieties of English can include formal or informal styles, distinguished by word choice and syntax, and they use both technical and non‑technical registers.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The settlement history of the English‑speaking inner‑circle countries outside Britain helped to level dialect distinctions and produce koiné forms of English in South Africa, Australia, and New Zealand.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The majority of immigrants to the United States without British ancestry rapidly adopted English after arrival.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Now the majority of the United States population are monolingual English speakers.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Modern English is sometimes described as the first global lingua franca, or as the first world language.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] English is the world's most widely used language in newspaper publishing, book publishing, international telecommunications, scientific publishing, international trade, mass entertainment, and diplomacy.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Parity with French as a language of diplomacy had been achieved by the Treaty of Versailles negotiations in 1919.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] By the time the United Nations was founded at the end of the Second World War, English had become pre‑eminent; it is one of the six official languages of the United Nations and is now the main worldwide language of diplomacy and international relations.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Many other worldwide international organisations, including the International Olympic Committee, specify English as a working language or official language of the organisation.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] While the EU allows member states to designate any of the national languages as an official language of the Union, in practice English is the main working language of EU organisations.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] English serves as the basis for the required controlled natural languages Seaspeak and Airspeak, used as international languages of seafaring and aviation.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] English is the most frequently taught foreign language in the world.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Most people learning English do so for practical reasons, as opposed to ideological ones.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In EU countries, English is the most widely spoken foreign language in 19 of the 25 member states where it is not an official language (that is, the countries other than Ireland and Malta).
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In a 2012 official Eurobarometer poll (conducted when the UK was still a member of the EU), 38 per cent of EU respondents outside the countries where English is an official language said they could speak English well enough to have a conversation in that language.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The next most commonly mentioned foreign language, French (which is the most widely known foreign language in the UK and Ireland), could be used in conversation by 12 per cent of respondents.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Working knowledge of English has become a requirement in a number of occupations and professions, such as medicine and computing.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Though it formerly had parity with French and German in scientific research, English now dominates the field.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] As decolonisation proceeded throughout the British Empire in the 1950s and 1960s, former colonies often did not reject English but rather continued to use it as independent countries setting their own language policies.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] For example, English is one of the official languages of India.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Many Indians have shifted from associating the language with colonialism to associating it with economic progress.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] English is widely used in media and literature, with India being the third‑largest publisher of English‑language books in the world, after the US and the UK.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] However, fewer than 5 per cent of the population speak English fluently, with the country's native English speakers numbering in the low hundreds of thousands.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In 2004, David Crystal claimed that India had the largest population of people able to speak or understand English in the world, though most scholars estimate that the US remains home to a larger English‑speaking population.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Many English speakers in Africa have become part of an 'Afro‑Saxon' language community that unites Africans from different countries.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Regarding its future development, it is considered most likely that English will continue to function as a koiné language, with a standard form that unifies speakers around the world.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Dialectologists identify many English dialects, which usually refer to regional varieties that differ from each other in terms of patterns of grammar, vocabulary, and pronunciation.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The pronunciation of particular areas distinguishes dialects as separate regional accents.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The major native dialects of English are often divided by linguists into two extremely general categories: British English (BrE) and North American English (NAE).
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The fact that English has been spoken in England for 1,500 years explains why England has a great wealth of regional dialects.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Within the United Kingdom, Received Pronunciation (RP), an educated accent associated originally with South East England, has been traditionally used as a broadcast standard and is considered the most prestigious of British accents.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The spread of RP (also known as BBC English) through the media has caused many traditional dialects of rural England to recede, as youths adopt the traits of the prestige variety instead of those from local dialects.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] At the time of the 1950–61 Survey of English Dialects, grammar and vocabulary differed across the country, but a process of lexical attrition has led most of this variation to disappear.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Nonetheless, this attrition has mostly affected dialectal variation in grammar and vocabulary.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Only 3% of the English population actually speak RP, with the remainder speaking in regional accents and dialects with varying degrees of RP influence.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] There is also variability within RP, particularly along class lines between upper‑ and middle‑class RP speakers, and between native RP speakers and those who adopt RP later in life.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Within Britain, there is also considerable variation along lines of social class; some traits, though exceedingly common, are nonetheless considered 'non‑standard' and associated with lower‑class speakers and identities.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] An example of this is *h*-dropping, which was historically a feature of lower‑class London English, particularly Cockney, and can now be heard in the local accents of most parts of England.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] However, it remains largely absent from broadcasting and among the upper crust of British society.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] English in England can be divided into four major dialect regions: South East English, South West English (also known as West Country English), Midlands English, and Northern English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Having been the centre of Danish occupation during the Viking invasions of England, Northern English dialects, particularly the Yorkshire dialect, retain Norse features not found in other English varieties.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In the West Midlands, dialects such as Black Country (Yam Yam), and to a lesser extent Birmingham (Brummie), preserve archaic features from Early Modern and Middle English, retaining Germanic elements such as specific grammatical structures and vocabulary.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Since the 15th century, South East England varieties have centred on London, which has been the centre from which dialectal innovations have spread to other dialects.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In London, the Cockney dialect was traditionally used by the lower classes, and it was long a socially stigmatised variety.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The spread of Cockney features across the South East led the media to talk of Estuary English as a new dialect, but the notion was criticised by many linguists on the grounds that London had been influencing neighbouring regions throughout history.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Scots is today considered a separate language from English, but it has its origins in early Northern Middle English and developed and changed during its history with influence from other sources, particularly Scottish Gaelic and Old Norse.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Scots itself has a number of regional dialects.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In addition to Scots, Scottish English comprises the varieties of Standard English spoken in Scotland; most varieties are Northern English accents, with some influence from Scots.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In Ireland, various forms of English have been spoken following the Norman invasion of the island during the 11th century.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In County Wexford and the area surrounding Dublin, two extinct dialects known as Forth and Bargy and Fingallian developed as offshoots from Early Middle English and were spoken until the 19th century.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Modern Irish English, however, has its roots in English colonisation in the 17th century.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Today Irish English is divided into Ulster English (the Northern Ireland dialect with strong influence from Scots) and various other dialects of Ireland.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Like Scottish and most North American accents, almost all Irish accents preserve the rhoticity that has been lost in the dialects influenced by RP.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Due to the relatively strong degree of mixing, mutual accommodation, and koinéisation that occurred during the colonial period, North American English has traditionally been perceived as relatively homogeneous, at least in comparison with British dialects.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] However, modern scholars have strongly opposed this notion, arguing that North American English shows a great deal of phonetic, lexical, and geographic variability.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] This becomes all the more apparent considering social, ethnolinguistic, and regional varieties such as African-American English, Chicano English, Cajun English, or Newfoundland English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Canadian English varieties, excepting those from Atlantic Canada and possibly Quebec, are generally considered to belong to the GA continuum, although they often show raising of the vowels /aɪ/ and /aʊ/ before voiceless consonants and have distinct norms for writing and pronunciation as well.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Atlantic Canadian English, notably distinct from Standard Canadian English, comprises Maritime English and Newfoundland English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] It was influenced mostly by British and Irish English, as well as Irish, Scottish Gaelic, and Acadian French.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In most American and Canadian English dialects, rhoticity (or *r*-fullness) is dominant, with non-rhoticity (or *r*-dropping) being associated with lower prestige and social class, especially since the end of World War II.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] This contrasts with the situation in England, where non-rhoticity has become the standard.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Varieties beyond GA which have developed distinct sound systems include the Southern American English, New York City English, Eastern New England English, and African-American Vernacular English (AAVE) groups – all of which are historically non-rhotic, save a few varieties of Southern American.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In Southern American English, the most populous grouping outside GA, rhoticity now strongly prevails, replacing the region's historical non-rhotic prestige.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Spoken primarily by working- and middle-class African Americans, African-American Vernacular English (AAVE) is largely non-rhotic, and likely originated among enslaved Africans and African Americans influenced primarily by the non-standard older Southern dialects.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] A minority of linguists, contrarily, propose that AAVE mostly traces back to African languages spoken by the slaves who had to develop a pidgin or English-based creole to communicate with slaves of other ethnic and linguistic origins.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] AAVE's important commonalities with Southern accents suggest it developed into a highly coherent and homogeneous variety in the 19th or early 20th century.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] AAVE is commonly stigmatised in North America as a form of "broken" or "uneducated" English, as are white Southern accents, but linguists today recognise both as fully developed varieties of English with their own norms shared by large speech communities.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Since 1788, English has been spoken in Oceania, and Australian English has developed as the first language of the vast majority of the inhabitants of the Australian continent, its standard accent being General Australian.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The English of neighbouring New Zealand has, to a lesser degree, become an influential standard variety of the language.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Australian and New Zealand English are each other's closest relatives, with few differentiating characteristics, followed by South African English and the English of South East England, all of which have similarly non‑rhotic accents (aside from some accents in the South Island of New Zealand).
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Australian and New Zealand English stand out for their innovative vowels: many short vowels are fronted or raised, whereas many long vowels have been diphthongised.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Australian English also has a contrast between long and short vowels that is not found in most other varieties.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Australian English grammar aligns closely with British and American English; like American English, collective plural subjects take a singular verb – for example, "the government is" (rather than 'are').
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] New Zealand English uses front vowels that are often even higher than those in Australian English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] English is an official language of the Philippines.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Its use is ubiquitous in the country, appearing on street signs, marquees, and government documents, as well as in courtrooms, public media, the entertainment industry, and the business sector.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] It became an important and widely spoken language in the country during the period of American rule between 1898 and 1946.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Taglish is a prominent form of code-switching between Tagalog and English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] English is spoken widely in southern Africa and is an official or co‑official language in several of the region's countries.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In South Africa, English has been spoken since 1820, co‑existing with Afrikaans and various African languages such as the Khoe and Bantu languages.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Today, about nine per cent of the South African population speaks South African English (SAE) as a first language.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] SAE is a non‑rhotic variety that tends to follow RP as a norm.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] It is one of the few non‑rhotic English varieties that lack intrusive R.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The second‑language varieties of South Africa differ according to the native languages of their speakers.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Most phonological differences from RP are in the vowels.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Consonantal differences include the tendency to pronounce /p, t, t͡ʃ, k/ without aspiration (e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] *pin* pronounced [pɪn] rather than [pʰɪn] as in most other varieties), while 'r' is often pronounced as a flap [ɾ] instead of as the more common fricative.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Nigerian English is a variety of English spoken in Nigeria; over 150 million Nigerians speak some form of the language.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Though traditionally based on British English, increasing United States influence during the latter part of the 20th century has resulted in American English vocabulary entering Nigerian English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Additionally, some new words and collocations have emerged from the variety out of a need to express concepts specific to the nation's culture (e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Varieties of English are spoken throughout the former British colonial possessions in the Caribbean, including Jamaica, the Leeward and Windward Islands, Trinidad and Tobago, Barbados, the Cayman Islands, and Belize.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Each of these areas is home both to a local variety of English and a local English‑based creole, combining English and African languages.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The most prominent varieties are Jamaican English and Jamaican Creole.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] In Central America, English‑based creoles are spoken on the Caribbean coasts of Nicaragua and Panama.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Residents are often fluent in both the local English variety and the local creole languages, and frequently code-switch between them.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The relationship between different varieties can be conceptualised as a continuum, in which more creole‑like or RP‑like forms function as more formal and informal registers of the language respectively.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Most Caribbean varieties are based on British English and, consequently, most are non‑rhotic, except for formal styles of Jamaican English, which are often rhotic.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Jamaican English differs from RP in its vowel inventory, which has a distinction between long and short vowels rather than tense and lax vowels as in Standard English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] The diphthongs /ei/ and /ou/ are monophthongs [eː] and [oː] or even the reverse diphthongs [ie] and [uo] (e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] *bay* and *boat* pronounced [bʲeː] and [bʷoːt]).
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Often, word‑final consonant clusters are simplified so that "child" is pronounced [t͡ʃail] and "wind" [win].
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Indian English historically tends towards RP as an ideal, with the proximity of speakers to RP generally reflecting class distinctions.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Indian English accents are marked by the pronunciation of phonemes such as /t/ and /d/ (often pronounced with retroflex articulation as [ʈ] and [ɖ]) and the replacement of /θ/ and /ð/ with dentals [t̪] and [d̪].
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Sometimes Indian English speakers may also use spelling‑based pronunciations, where the silent ⟨h⟩ found in words such as *ghost* is pronounced as an Indian voiced aspirated stop [ɡʱ].
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] Non‑native English speakers may pronounce words differently because they have not fully mastered English pronunciation.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] This can happen either because they apply the speech rules of their mother tongue to English ('interference') or because they implement strategies similar to those used in first language acquisition.
[src:english-language/english-language-p01] They may create novel pronunciations for English sounds that do not exist in their first language.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English phonology and phonetics differ from one dialect to another, usually without interfering with mutual communication.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Phonological variation affects the inventory of phonemes (speech sounds that distinguish meaning), and phonetic variation consists in differences in pronunciation of the phonemes.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] This overview mainly describes Received Pronunciation (RP) and General American (GA), the standard varieties of the United Kingdom and the United States respectively.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Most English dialects share the same 24 consonant phonemes (or 26, if marginal /x/ and glottal stop /ʔ/ are included).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The consonant inventory shown below is valid for California English, and for RP.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] For pairs of obstruents (stops, affricates, and fricatives) such as /p b/, /tʃ dʒ/, and /s z/, the first is fortis (strong) and the second is lenis (weak).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Fortis obstruents, such as /p tʃ s/ are pronounced with more muscular tension and breath force than lenis consonants, such as /b dʒ z/, and are always voiceless.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Lenis consonants are partly voiced at the beginning and end of utterances, and fully voiced between vowels.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Fortis stops such as /p/ have additional articulatory or acoustic features in most dialects: they are aspirated [pʰ] when they occur alone at the beginning of a stressed syllable, often unaspirated in other cases, and often unreleased [p̚] or pre-glottalised [ʔp] at the end of a syllable.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] In a single-syllable word, a vowel before a fortis stop is shortened: e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] *nip* has a noticeably shorter vowel (phonetically, not phonemically) than *nib* [nɪˑb̥] (see below).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] In RP, the lateral approximant /l/ has two main allophones (pronunciation variants): the clear or plain [l], as in *light*, and the dark or velarised [ɫ], as in *full*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] All sonorants (liquids /l, r/ and nasals /m, n, ŋ/) devoice when following a voiceless obstruent, and they are syllabic when following a consonant at the end of a word.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The pronunciation of vowels varies a great deal between dialects and is one of the most detectable aspects of a speaker's accent.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The accompanying table below lists the vowel phonemes in RP and GA, with example words from lexical sets.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The vowels are represented with symbols from the International Phonetic Alphabet; those given for RP are standard in British dictionaries and other publications.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] In RP, vowel length is phonemic; long vowels are marked with a triangular colon ⟨ː⟩ in the table above, such as the vowel of *need* [niːd] as opposed to *bid* [bɪd].
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Because lenis consonants are frequently voiceless at the end of a syllable, vowel length is an important cue as to whether the following consonant is lenis or fortis.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The vowel /ə/ only occurs in unstressed syllables and is more open in quality in stem-final positions.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Some dialects do not contrast /ɪ/ and /ə/ in unstressed positions, such that *rabbit* and *abbot* rhyme and *Lenin* and *Lennon* are homophonous, a dialectal feature called the weak vowel merger.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] GA /ɜr/ and /ər/ are realised as an *r*-coloured vowel [ɚ], as in *further* [ˈfɚðɚ] (phonemically /ˈfɜrðər/), which in RP is realised as [ˈfəːðə] (phonemically /ˈfɜːðə/).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] An English syllable includes a syllable nucleus consisting of a vowel sound.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Syllable onset and coda (start and end) are optional.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] A syllable can start with up to three consonant sounds, as in *sprint* /sprɪnt/, and end with up to five, as in (for some dialects) *angsts* /aŋksts/.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] This gives an English syllable a structure of (CCC)V(CCCCC) – where C represents a consonant and V a vowel.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The word *strengths* /strɛŋθs/ is thus close to the most complex syllable possible in English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The consonants that may appear together in onsets or codas are restricted, as is the order in which they may appear.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Onsets can only have four types of consonant clusters: a stop and approximant, as in *play*; a voiceless fricative and approximant, as in *fly* or *sly*; *s* and a voiceless stop, as in *stay*; and *s*, a voiceless stop, and an approximant, as in *string*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Clusters of nasal and stop are only allowed in codas.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Clusters of obstruents always agree in voicing, and clusters of sibilants and of plosives with the same point of articulation are prohibited.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Several consonants have limited distributions: /h/ can only occur in syllable-initial position, and /ŋ/ only in syllable-final position.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Stress plays an important role in English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Certain syllables are stressed, while others are unstressed.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Stress is a combination of duration, intensity, vowel quality, and sometimes changes in pitch.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Stressed syllables are pronounced longer and louder than unstressed syllables, and vowels in unstressed syllables are frequently reduced while vowels in stressed syllables are not.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Stress in English is phonemic, gaining freedom and dynamicity once lost in Proto-Germanic through a majority of borrowings from non-Germanic languages.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] For instance, the word *contract* is stressed on the first syllable (/ˈkɒntrækt/ *KON-trakt*) when used as a noun, but on the last syllable (/kənˈtrækt/ *kən-TRAKT*) for most meanings (for example, "reduce in size") when used as a verb.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Here stress is connected to vowel reduction: in the noun "contract" the first syllable is stressed and has the unreduced vowel /ɒ/, but in the verb "contract" the first syllable is unstressed and its vowel is reduced to /ə/.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Stress is also used to distinguish between words and phrases, so that a compound word receives a single stress unit, but the corresponding phrase has two: e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] "a burnout" (/ˈbɜːrnaʊt/) versus "to burn out" (/ˈbɜːrn ˈaʊt/), and "a hotdog" (/ˈhɒtdɒɡ/) versus "a hot dog" (/ˈhɒt ˈdɒɡ/).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] In terms of rhythm, English is generally described as a stress-timed language, meaning that the amount of time between stressed syllables tends to be equal.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Stressed syllables are pronounced longer, but unstressed syllables (syllables between stresses) are shortened.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Vowels in unstressed syllables are shortened as well, and vowel shortening causes changes in vowel quality: vowel reduction.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Varieties of English vary the most in pronunciation of vowels.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The best-known national varieties used as standards for education in non-English-speaking countries are British (BrE) and American (AmE).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Countries such as Canada, Australia, Ireland, New Zealand and South Africa have their own standard varieties which are less often used as standards for education internationally.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English has undergone many historical sound changes, some of them affecting all varieties, and others affecting only a few.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Most standard varieties are affected by the Great Vowel Shift, which changed the pronunciation of long vowels, but a few dialects have slightly different results.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] In North America, a number of chain shifts such as the Northern Cities Vowel Shift and Canadian Shift have produced very different vowel landscapes in some regional accents.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Some dialects have fewer or more consonant phonemes and phones than the standard varieties.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Some conservative varieties like Scottish English have a voiceless [ʍ] sound in *whine* that contrasts with the voiced [w] in *wine*, but most other dialects pronounce both words with voiced [w], a dialect feature called *wine*–*whine* merger.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The voiceless velar fricative sound /x/ is found in Scottish English, which distinguishes *loch* /lɔx/ from *lock* /lɔk/.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Other changes affecting the phonology of local varieties are processes such as *yod*-dropping, *yod*-coalescence, and reduction of consonant clusters.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] GA and RP vary in their pronunciation of historical /r/ after a vowel at the end of a syllable (in the syllable coda).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] GA is a rhotic dialect, meaning that it pronounces /r/ at the end of a syllable, but RP is non-rhotic, meaning that it loses /r/ in that position.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English dialects are classified as rhotic or non-rhotic depending on whether they elide /r/ like RP or keep it like GA.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] There is complex dialectal variation in words with the open front and open back vowels /æ ɑː ɒ ɔː/.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] These four vowels are only distinguished in RP, Australia, New Zealand and South Africa.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] In GA, these vowels merge to three /æ ɑ ɔ/, and in Canadian English, they merge to two /æ ɑ/.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Since the 9th century, English has been written using the English alphabet, which uses the Latin script.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Anglo-Saxon runes were previously used to write Old English, but only in short inscriptions; the overwhelming majority of attested writings in Old English are in the Old English Latin alphabet.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English orthography is multi-layered and complex, with elements of French, Latin, and Greek spelling on top of the native Germanic system.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Further complications have arisen through sound changes with which the orthography has not kept pace.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Compared to European languages for which official organisations have promoted spelling reforms, English has spelling that is a less consistent indicator of pronunciation, and standard spellings of words that are more difficult to guess from knowing how a word is pronounced.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] There are also systematic spelling differences between British and American English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] These situations have prompted proposals for spelling reform in English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Although letters and speech sounds do not have a one-to-one correspondence in standard English spelling, spelling rules that take into account syllable structure, phonetic changes in derived words, and word accent are reliable for most English words.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Moreover, standard English spelling shows etymological relationships between related words that would be obscured by a closer correspondence between pronunciation and spelling – for example, the words *photograph*, *photography*, and *photographic*, or the words *electricity* and *electrical*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] While few scholars agree with Chomsky and Halle (1968) that conventional English orthography is "near-optimal", there is a rationale for current English spelling patterns.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The standard orthography of English is the most widely used writing system in the world.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Standard English spelling is based on a graphomorphemic segmentation of words into written clues of what meaningful units make up each word.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Readers of English can generally rely on the correspondence between spelling and pronunciation to be fairly regular for letters or digraphs used to spell consonant sounds.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The letters *c* and *g* normally represent /k/ and /ɡ/, but there is also a soft *c* pronounced /s/, and a soft *g* pronounced /dʒ/.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The differences in the pronunciations of the letters *c* and *g* are often signalled by the following letters in standard English spelling.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Digraphs used to represent phonemes and phoneme sequences include *ch* for /tʃ/, *sh* for /ʃ/, *th* for /θ/ or /ð/, *ng* for /ŋ/, *qu* for /kw/, and *ph* for /f/ in Greek-derived words.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The single letter *x* is generally pronounced as /z/ in word-initial position and as /ks/ otherwise.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] For the vowel sounds of the English language, however, correspondences between spelling and pronunciation are more irregular.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] There are many more vowel phonemes in English than there are single vowel letters (*a*, *e*, *i*, *o*, *u*, *y*, and very rarely *w*).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] As a result, some "long vowels" are often indicated by combinations of letters (like the *oa* in *boat*, the *ow* in *how*, and the *ay* in *stay*), or the historically based silent *e* (as in *note* and *cake*).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The consequence of this complex orthographic history is that learning to read and write can be challenging in English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] It can take longer for school pupils to become independently fluent readers of English than of many other languages, including Italian, Spanish, and German.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Nonetheless, there is an advantage for learners of English reading in learning the specific sound-symbol regularities that occur in the standard English spellings of commonly used words.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Such instruction greatly reduces the risk of children experiencing reading difficulties in English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Making primary school teachers more aware of the primacy of morpheme representation in English may help learners learn more efficiently to read and write English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English writing also includes a system of punctuation marks that is similar to those used in most alphabetic languages around the world.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The purpose of punctuation is to mark meaningful grammatical relationships in sentences to aid readers in understanding a text and to indicate features important for reading a text aloud.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Typical for an Indo-European language, English grammar follows accusative morphosyntactic alignment.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Unlike other Indo-European languages, English has largely abandoned the inflectional case system in favour of analytic constructions.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Only the personal pronouns retain morphological case more strongly than any other word class.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English distinguishes at least seven major word classes: verbs, nouns, adjectives, adverbs, determiners (including articles), prepositions, and conjunctions.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Some analyses add pronouns as a class separate from nouns, and subdivide conjunctions into subordinators and coordinators, and add the class of interjections.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English also has a rich set of auxiliary verbs, such as *have* and *do*, expressing the categories of mood and aspect.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Questions are marked by *do*-support, *wh*-movement (fronting of question words beginning with *wh*-) and word order inversion with some verbs.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Vestiges of the case and gender system are found in the pronoun system (*he* / *him*, *who* / *whom*); similarly, traces of more complex verb conjugation are seen in the inflection of the copula verb *to be*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English nouns are only inflected for number and possession.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] New nouns can be formed through derivation or compounding.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] They are semantically divided into proper nouns (names) and common nouns.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Common nouns are in turn divided into concrete and abstract nouns, and grammatically into count nouns and mass nouns.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Most count nouns are inflected for plural number through the use of the plural suffix -*s*, but a few nouns have irregular plural forms.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Mass nouns can only be pluralised through the use of a count noun classifier, e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] "one loaf of bread", "two loaves of bread".
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Possession can be expressed either by the possessive enclitic -*s* (also traditionally called a genitive suffix), or by the preposition *of*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Historically the -*s* possessive has been used for animate nouns, whereas the *of* possessive has been reserved for inanimate nouns.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Today this distinction is less clear, and many speakers use -*s* also with inanimates.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Orthographically the possessive -*s* is separated from a singular noun with an apostrophe.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] If the noun is plural formed with -*s* the apostrophe follows the -*s*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Nouns can form noun phrases (NPs) where they are the syntactic head of the words that depend on them such as determiners, quantifiers, conjunctions or adjectives.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Noun phrases can be short, such as *the man*, composed only of a determiner and a noun.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] They can also include modifiers such as adjectives (e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] *red*, *tall*, *all*) and specifiers such as determiners (e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] But they can also tie together several nouns into a single long NP, using conjunctions such as *and*, or prepositions such as *with*, e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] "the tall man with the long red trousers and his skinny wife with the spectacles" (this NP uses conjunctions, prepositions, specifiers, and modifiers).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Regardless of length, an NP functions as a syntactic unit.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] For example, the possessive enclitic can, in cases which do not lead to ambiguity, follow the entire noun phrase, as in "The President of India's wife", where the enclitic follows *India* and not *President*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The class of determiners is used to specify the noun they precede in terms of definiteness, where *the* marks a definite noun and *a* or *an* marks an indefinite one.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] A definite noun is assumed by the speaker to be already known by the interlocutor, whereas an indefinite noun is not specified as being previously known.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Quantifiers, which include *one*, *many*, *some* and *all*, are used to specify the noun in terms of quantity or number.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The noun must agree with the number of the determiner, e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Determiners are the first constituents in a noun phrase.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English adjectives are words such as *good*, *big*, *interesting*, and *Canadian* that most typically modify nouns, denoting characteristics of their referents (e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] As modifiers, they come before the nouns they modify and after determiners.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English adjectives also function as predicative complements (e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] In Modern English, adjectives are not inflected so as to agree in form with the noun they modify, as in most other Indo-European languages.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] For example, in the phrases "the slender boy", and "many slender girls", the adjective *slender* does not change form to agree with either the number or gender of the noun.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Some adjectives are inflected for degree of comparison, with the positive degree unmarked, the suffix -*er* marking the comparative, and -*est* marking the superlative: "a small boy", "the boy is smaller than the girl", "that boy is the smallest".
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Some adjectives have irregular suppletive comparative and superlative forms, such as *good*, *better*, and *best*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Other adjectives have comparatives formed by periphrastic constructions, with the adverb *more* marking the comparative, and *most* marking the superlative: *happier* or *more happy*, *the happiest* or *most happy*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] There is some variation among speakers regarding which adjectives use inflected or periphrastic comparison, and some studies have shown a tendency for the periphrastic forms to become more common at the expense of the inflected form.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English determiners are words such as *the*, *each*, *many*, *some*, and *which*, occurring most typically in noun phrases before the head nouns and any modifiers and marking the noun phrase as definite or indefinite.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] They often agree with the noun in number.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] They do not typically inflect for degree of comparison.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English pronouns conserve many traits of case and gender inflection.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The subjective case corresponds to the Old English nominative case, and the objective case is used in the sense both of the previous accusative case (for a patient, or direct object of a transitive verb), and of the Old English dative case (for a recipient or indirect object of a transitive verb).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The subjective is used when the pronoun is the subject of a finite clause, otherwise the objective is used.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Possessive pronouns exist in dependent and independent forms; the dependent form functions as a determiner specifying a noun (as in *my chair*), while the independent form can stand alone as if it were a noun (e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Grammatical person in English no longer distinguishes between formal and informal pronouns of address, with the second person singular familiar pronoun *thou* that previously existed in the language having fallen almost entirely out of use by the 18th century.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Pronouns are used to refer to entities deictically or anaphorically.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] A deictic pronoun points to some person or object by identifying it relative to the speech situation – for example, the pronoun *I* identifies the speaker, and the pronoun *you*, the addressee.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Anaphoric pronouns such as *that* refer back to an entity already mentioned or assumed by the speaker to be known by the audience, for example in the sentence "I already told you that".
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The reflexive pronouns are used when the oblique argument is identical to the subject of a phrase (e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] "he sent it to himself" or "she braced herself for impact").
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Prepositional phrases (PP) are phrases composed of a preposition and one or more nouns, e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] "with the dog", "for my friend", "to school", "in England".
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English prepositions have a wide range of uses – including describing movement, place, and other relations between entities, as well as functions that are syntactic in nature, like introducing complement clauses and oblique arguments of verbs.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] For example, in the phrase "I gave it to him", the preposition *to* marks the indirect object of the verb *to give*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Traditionally words were only considered prepositions if they governed the case of the noun they preceded, for example causing the pronouns to use the objective rather than subjective form, "with her", "to me", "for us".
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] But some contemporary grammars no longer consider government of case to be the defining feature of the class of prepositions, rather defining prepositions as words that can function as the heads of prepositional phrases.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English verbs are inflected for tense and aspect and marked for agreement with a third person present singular subject.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Only the copula verb *to be* is still inflected for agreement with the plural and first and second person subjects.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Auxiliary verbs such as *have* and *be* are paired with verbs in the infinitive, past, or progressive forms.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] They form complex tenses, aspects, and moods.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Auxiliary verbs differ from other verbs in that they can be followed by the negation, and in that they can occur as the first constituent in a question sentence.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The primary forms are a plain present, a third person singular present, and a preterite (past) form.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The secondary forms are a plain form used for the infinitive, a gerund-participle and a past participle.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The verb *to be* – which among other uses in English functions as the primary auxiliary verb indicating the imperfective aspect (e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] "I *am* going"), as well as the copula – is the only verb to retain some of its original conjugation, and takes different inflectional forms depending on the subject.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The first person present form is *am*, the third person singular form is *is*, and the form *are* is used in the second person singular and all three plurals.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The only verb past participle is *been* and its gerund-participle is *being*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English has two primary tenses, past (preterite) and non-past.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The preterite is inflected by using the preterite form of the verb, which for the regular verbs includes the suffix *-ed*, and for the strong verbs either the suffix *-t* or a change in the stem vowel.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The non-past form is unmarked except in the third person singular, which takes the suffix *-s*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English does not have future verb forms.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The future tense is expressed periphrastically with one of the auxiliary verbs *will* or *shall*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Many varieties also use a near future constructed with the phrasal verb "be going to" (going-to future).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Further aspectual distinctions are shown by auxiliary verbs, primarily *have* and *be*, which show the contrast between a perfect and non-perfect past tense ("I have run" vs.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] "I was running"), and compound tenses such as preterite perfect ("I had been running") and present perfect ("I have been running").
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] For the expression of mood, English uses a number of modal auxiliaries, such as *can*, *may*, *will*, *shall* and the past tense forms *could*, *might*, *would*, *should*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] There are also subjunctive and imperative moods, both based on the plain form of the verb (i.e. without the third person singular *-s*), for use in subordinate clauses (e.g. subjunctive: "It is important that he run every day"; imperative *Run!*).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] An infinitive form, that uses the plain form of the verb and the preposition *to*, is used for verbal clauses that are syntactically subordinate to a finite verbal clause.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Finite verbal clauses are those that are formed around a verb in the present or preterite form.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] In clauses with auxiliary verbs, they are the finite verbs and the main verb is treated as a subordinate clause.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] For example, "he has to go" where only the auxiliary verb *have* is inflected for time and the main verb *to go* is in the infinitive, or in a complement clause such as "I saw him leave", where the main verb is *see*, which is in a preterite form, and *leave* is in the infinitive.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English also makes frequent use of constructions traditionally called phrasal verbs, verb phrases that are made up of a verb root and a preposition or particle that follows the verb.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The phrase then functions as a single predicate.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] In terms of intonation the preposition is fused to the verb, but in writing it is written as a separate word.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Examples of phrasal verbs are "to get up", "to ask out", "to get together", and "to put up with".
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The phrasal verb frequently has a highly idiomatic meaning that is more specialised and restricted than what can be simply extrapolated from the combination of verb and preposition complement (e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] *lay off* meaning *terminate someone's employment*).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Some grammarians do not consider this type of construction to form a syntactic constituent and hence refrain from using the term "phrasal verb".
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Instead, they consider the construction simply to be a verb with a prepositional phrase as its syntactic complement, e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] "he woke up in the morning" and "he ran up in the mountains" are syntactically equivalent.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The function of adverbs is to modify the action or event described by the verb by providing additional information about the manner in which it occurs.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Many English adverbs are derived from adjectives by appending the suffix *-ly*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] For example, in the phrase "the woman walked quickly", the adverb *quickly* is derived from the adjective *quick*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Some commonly used adjectives have irregular adverbial forms, such as *good*, which has the adverbial form *well*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Modern English syntax is moderately analytic.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] It has developed features such as modal verbs and word order as resources for conveying meaning.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Auxiliary verbs mark constructions such as questions, negative polarity, the passive voice and progressive aspect.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English has moved from the Germanic verb-second (V2) word order to being almost exclusively subject–verb–object (SVO).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The combination of SVO order and use of auxiliary verbs often creates clusters of two or more verbs at the centre of the sentence, such as "he had been hoping to try opening it".
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] In most sentences, English only marks grammatical relations through word order.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The subject constituent precedes the verb and the object constituent follows it.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Indirect objects (IO) of ditransitive verbs can be placed either as the first object in a double object construction (S V IO O), such as "I gave *Jane* the book" or in a prepositional phrase, such as "I gave the book *to Jane*".
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English sentences may be composed of one or more clauses, that may in turn be composed of one or more phrases (e.g. noun phrases, verb phrases, prepositional phrases).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] A clause is built around a verb and includes its constituents, such as any noun or prepositional phrases.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Within a sentence, there is always at least one main clause (or matrix clause) whereas other clauses are subordinate to a main clause.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Subordinate clauses may function as arguments of the verb in the main clause.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] For example, in the phrase "I think (that) you are lying", the main clause is headed by the verb *think*, the subject is *I*, but the object of the phrase is the subordinate clause "(that) you are lying".
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The subordinating conjunction *that* shows that the clause that follows is a subordinate clause, but it is often omitted.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Relative clauses can be introduced by the pronouns *who*, *whose*, *whom*, and *which* as well as by *that* (which can also be omitted).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] In contrast to many other Germanic languages there are no major differences between word order in main and subordinate clauses.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] English auxiliary verbs are relied upon for many functions, including the expression of tense, aspect, and mood.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Auxiliary verbs form main clauses, and the main verbs function as heads of a subordinate clause of the auxiliary verb.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] For example, in the sentence "the dog did not find its bone", the clause "find its bone" is the complement of the negated verb *did not*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Subject–auxiliary inversion is used in many constructions, including focus, negation, and interrogative constructions.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Negation is done with the adverb *not*, which precedes the main verb and follows an auxiliary verb.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] A contracted form of not -*n't* can be used as an enclitic attaching to auxiliary verbs and to the copula verb *to be*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Just as with questions, many negative constructions require the negation to occur with *do*-support, thus in Modern English "I don't know him" is the correct answer to the question "Do you know him?", but not *"I know him not", although this construction may be found in older English.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Passive constructions also use auxiliary verbs.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] A passive construction rephrases an active construction in such a way that the object of the active phrase becomes the subject of the passive phrase, and the subject of the active phrase is either omitted or demoted to a role as an oblique argument introduced in a prepositional phrase.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] They are formed by using the past participle either with the auxiliary verb *to be* or *to get*, although not all varieties of English allow the use of passives with *get*.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] For example, putting the sentence "she sees him" into the passive becomes "he is seen (by her)", or "he gets seen (by her)".
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Both yes/no questions and *wh*-questions in English are mostly formed using subject–auxiliary inversion ("Am I going tomorrow?", "Where can we eat?"), which may require *do*-support ("Do you like her?", "Where did he go?").
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] In most cases, interrogative words (or wh*-words*) – which include *who*, *what*, *when*, *where*, *why*, and *how* – appear in a fronted position.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] For example, in the question "What did you see?", the word *what* appears as the first constituent despite being the grammatical object of the sentence.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] When the *wh*-word is the subject or forms part of the subject, no inversion occurs (e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Prepositional phrases can also be fronted when they are the questions theme (e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] "To whose house did you go last night?").
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The personal interrogative pronoun *who* is the only interrogative pronoun to still show inflection for case, with the variant *whom* serving as the objective case form, although this form may be going out of use in many contexts.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] While English is a subject-prominent language, at the discourse level it tends to use a topic–comment structure, where the known information (topic) precedes the new information (comment).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Because of the strict SVO syntax, the topic of a sentence generally has to be the grammatical subject of the sentence.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] In cases where the topic is not the grammatical subject of the sentence, it is often promoted to subject position through syntactic means.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] One way of doing this is through a passive construction, "the girl was stung by the bee".
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Another way is through a cleft sentence where the main clause is demoted to be a complement clause of a copula sentence with a dummy subject such as *it* or *there*, e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] "it was the girl that the bee stung", "there was a girl who was stung by a bee".
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Dummy subjects are also used in constructions where there is no grammatical subject such as with impersonal verbs (e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] "it is raining") or in existential clauses ("there are many cars on the street").
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Through the use of these complex sentence constructions with informationally vacuous subjects, English is able to maintain both a topic–comment sentence structure and a SVO syntax.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Focus constructions emphasise a particular piece of new or salient information within a sentence, generally through allocating the main sentence level stress on the focal constituent.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] For example, "the girl was stung by *a bee*" (emphasising it was a bee and not, for example, a wasp that stung her), or "*the girl* was stung by a bee" (contrasting with another possibility, for example that it was the boy).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Topic and focus can also be established through syntactic dislocation, either preposing or postposing the item to be focused on relative to the main clause.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] For example, "That girl over there, she was stung by a bee", emphasises the girl by preposition, but a similar effect could be achieved by postposition, "she was stung by a bee, that girl over there", where reference to the girl is established as an afterthought.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Cohesion between sentences is achieved through the use of deictic pronouns as anaphora (e.g.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] "that is exactly what I mean" where *that* refers to some fact known to both interlocutors, or *then* used to locate the time of a narrated event relative to the time of a previously narrated event).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Discourse markers such as *oh*, *so*, or *well*, also signal the progression of ideas between sentences and help to create cohesion.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Discourse markers are often the first constituents in sentences.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] Discourse markers are also used for stance taking in which speakers position themselves in a specific attitude towards what is being said, for example, "no way is that true!" (the idiomatic marker "no way!" expressing disbelief), or "boy!
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] I'm hungry" (the marker *boy* expressing emphasis).
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] While discourse markers are particularly characteristic of informal and spoken registers of English, they are also used in written and formal registers.
[src:english-language/english-language-p02] The English lexicon consists of around 170,000 words (or 220,000, if counting obsolete words), according to an estimate based on the 1989 edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary*.
